<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Productivity Increases 0.8 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. productivity
increased by 0.8 percent in 1996, the best showing in four years,
the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the advance in the U.S. non-farm
productivity, which measures output per hour of work, was more
than double the 0.3 percent gain in 1995.
</P>
<P>
It is also the best showing since productivity shot up by 3.2
percent in 1992, the year after the 1990-91 recession.
</P>
<P>
However, it was far below the typical increase in the decades
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
The productivity in the U.S. often rose more than 2 percent a
year in the 1950s and 1960s. Since the early 1970s, its gains have
been averaging around 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. productivity at the end of last year improved
markedly. It was up by 2.2 percent in the final three months of
1996, the best in three years. The productivity was unchanged in
the third quarter, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The department said unit labor costs -- which take account of
both hourly wages and productivity -- rose at a 1.4 percent annual
rate in the fourth quarter, down from the 3.3 percent rise in the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
For the year, unit labor costs rose 2.9 percent, the same as in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The productivity is the key measurement oement in American
living standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
