<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Strongly Condemns Ethnic Violence in Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- France today "very strongly"
condemned the ethnic violence that took place in the Bosnian city
of Mostar, which Paris said was threatening the process of
reconciliation in the town divided between Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
"These incidents conflicted with the efforts made by the
international community and by the European Union in particular in
this city," said French Foreign Ministry vice-spokesman Yves
Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 200 French soldiers and 150 Spanish soldiers
belonging to the Stabilization Force (SFOR) of NATO have been
dispatched to Mostar to reinforce a Spanish unit of the SFOR and
prevent new clashes between Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted SFOR spokesman
Lieutenant-Colonel Bayle as saying in Mostar that a company of
French soldiers, backed by light armored vehicles, have been
patrolling the streets of Mostar and stationed at some places
considered as sensitive.
</P>
<P>
The reinforcement came after a Spanish unit of the SFOR failed
to put under control the violence between Muslims and Croats in a
Croat district of the city Monday.
</P>
<P>
The violence started after Croat police shot dead a Muslim man
to disperse a cortege of Muslims, who were going to a cemetery in
a Croat district to pay homage to the tombs of their parents
buried there, after the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
