<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Arrests Two Ruling Party Legislators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Two South Korean National
Assembly members of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) were arrested
by the prosecution here tonight on charges of taking graft and
exerting influence in connection with the Hanbo loan scandal.
</P>
<P>
Hong In-kil, who has been secretary to South Korean President
Kim Young-sam since the seventies, was accused of having received
a total of one million U.S. dollars from Hanbo Business Group
General Chairman Chung Tae-soo on four occasions last year -- with
the request that he exercised his influence on banks so that Hanbo
could obtain loans easily.
</P>
<P>
Chung Jae-chull, chairman of the NKP's national convention, was
charged with receiving 100,000 U.S. dollars from Chung Tae-soo in
October 1995.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported that the Hanbo leader asked Chung
Jae-chull to give money to the lawmakers of National Congress for
New Politics (NCNP), the main opposition in South Korea, hoping
they would promote banks giving loans to the Hanbo Iron and Steel
Company.
</P>
<P>
Chung Jae-chull allegedly handed the money to NCNP legislator
Kwon Roh-kap, conveying to him the message from the Hanbo leader.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prosecution issued a summons to Kwon Roh-kap
this afternoon, telling him to report to the prosecution by
tomorrow morning or face arrest.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said Chung Tae-soo poured huge amounts of money
into politicians' pockets in the process of financing his project
to set up a steel mill in South Korea's southern Chungchong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chung Tae-soo was arrested by the prosecution on January 31 on
charges of fraud and embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
He had secured six billion U.S. dollars in bank loans between
1992 and 1996 without sufficient collateral for his flagship firm,
Hanbo Iron and Steel Company. The company was declared bankrupt by
its creditors on January 23 after failing to honor billions of
U.S. dollars in notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
