<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   UK Tories Plan Major Education Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain will undergo education
reforms designed to raise and guarantee standards, British Prime
Minister John Major and Education and Employment Secretary Gillian
Shephard said today.
</P>
<P>
In the third of a series of pre-election press conferences
today, Major set out the Tories' plans for education reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said the nation's schools would be set targets each year to
improve the number of General Certificated Secondary Education
(GCSE) passes, and the levels of literacy and numeration.
</P>
<P>
At present, only 45 percent of 15-year-olds get five GCSEs at
grades between starred A and C.
</P>
<P>
The aim would be - over a number of years - to nearly double
that figure, said Major.
</P>
<P>
Higher targets would also be set for the testing of younger
children. Currently 57 percent of 14 year olds, 58 percent of 11
year olds, and 80 percent of seven year olds had achieved the
level set for their ages.
</P>
<P>
Schools would also have to set targets to allow comparisons to
be drawn with rivals and international standards. All parents
would be given information on how their children were doing at
school.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Shephard said that "All the Government's education reforms
were designed to raise and guarantee standards. The quality,
consistency and reputation of qualifications were a key part of
that drive on standards."
</P>
<P>
The annual report, published by British government last
February, said that Britain had suffered from a low standard
education system for decades. Standards needed to be raised in
half the 20,000 primary schools and two-fifths of the 3500
secondary schools,
</P>
<P>
Education reforms are one of focus topics in Britain before the
 general election due to be held in May this year. Both Tory and
Labor regard this as their priority.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Tony Blair promised on January 12 to make the
education of the nation's children his "first priority" if Labor
won the general election.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to revolutionize Britain's schools as
radically as Margaret Thatcher reformed trade union law in the
1980s. He said secondary school children would be required to do
at least 90 minutes' homework everyday, and seven to 11-year-olds,
30 minutes'. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
