<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Lobbyists Call for Road Safety Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The EU lobbyists have called
for mandatory speed limits on major European roads and random
breath tests as two of a package of safety initiatives to cut
20,000 from the European Union's annual road death toll, it was
learned today.
</P>
<P>
The call for safety measures came Monday from the European
Transport Safety Council as it started a campaign to get EU
governments committed to cutting annual road deaths from the
current 45,000 to 25,000 people by the year of 2005.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than half of those killed recently
have been car users, while those on two-wheeled motor vehicles and
pedestrians each accounted for about 15 percent of deaths.
</P>
<P>
Freddy Blak, a Danish member of the European Parliament, said
that two million people, mainly young people under the age of 25,
obtained driving licences each year but about 2,000 of them were
killed on the road within a year.
</P>
<P>
He is urging the European Commission to devise an action plan
"in response to this clearly unacceptable situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
