<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 10,000 Seek Asylum in Germany in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics released
today showed a total of 10,877 people applied for asylum in
Germany last month, with 6 percent of the applications approved.
</P>
<P>
The number of asylum seekers registered an increase of about
2,700 persons over December, probably due to seasonal causes,
according to the Federal Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Of these people, the largest group were Turkish nationals,
totaling about 2,300 persons. They were followed by more than
1,400 Iraqis and nearly 1,100 people from the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that after Bonn tightened control over
immigration in 1993, the number of asylum seekers in the country
dramatically reduced from a record 438,191 people in 1992 to
116,367 in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Rejects Israel's Proposal on Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today rejected a proposal by Israel on replacing Israeli troops
with a French inter-position contingent in southern Lebanon to
separate Israel from the pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Chirac was quoted as saying during a meeting with Lebanese
Prime Minister Rafic Hariri that France is opposed to a unilateral
solution to the conflict in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"France will not send inter-position troops to southern Lebanon
if the Israelis withdraw from there in a unilateral way," said
Hariri following his talks with Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese prime minister, who is a close friend of Chirac,
said that the position of France is that one should go back to the
negotiating table to seek a global peace agreement between Israel,
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the French presidential office said that Chirac
reaffirmed the "land for peace" principle for solving the Middle
East conflict, which he presented during his tour of the Middle
East last October.
</P>
<P>
Israelis Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu has ruled out the
possibility of withdrawing Israeli troops from the Golan Heights,
which Israel seized from Syria and annexed after the 1967 Middle
East war.
</P>
<P>
Some Israeli parliament members proposed last week that Israeli
troops withdraw from southern Lebanon and be replaced by a French
contingent, after a clash of two Israeli military helicopters
killed more than 70 Israeli soldiers in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador to Israel Jean-Noel de Bouillane de Lacoste
rejected the proposal, saying that Israel must sign a peace
agreement with Syria first.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Defense Minister Charles Millon will start an
official visit in Israel Wednesday to "renew" defense cooperation
between the two countries, which was first launched in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
