<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNITA Expels Former Polit-Bureau Member From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Angola's major opposition, the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has
announced to expel Fatima Roque, a former member of its political
bureau, from the party.
</P>
<P>
It also declared that Fatima, who was elected member of the
People's Assembly in September 1992 before the re-start of the
civil war, would not remain a UNITA member of the parliament,
according to the Angolan News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Fatima claimed she would not abandon her parliament
membership, but UNITA said the former party official, who fled to
the Portuguese capital of Lisbon in 1993 after the restart of the
civil war, had no right to remain a UNITA party member.
</P>
<P>
Only the UNITA leadership has the power to appoint its own
members to the parliament and the national unity government,
which are soon to be inaugurated, said the UNITA announcement,
adding that "any attempt to disrupt this practice would put the
peace at stake."
</P>
<P>
A UNITA announcement to this effect was also released in
Lisbon, where Fatima is still staying, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, UNITA also expelled Honorio Van-Dunem, Norberto De
Castro and Waldemar Correia, who were also elected members of the
People's Assembly in 1992, from the party, and dismissed their
UNITA parliament memberships.
</P>
<P>
Angola's much-delayed peace process is still moving ahead with
the formation of a united army nearly completed, UNITA members of
parliament soon to arrive at the capital, and differences
narrowed between the former rivals over power sharing in the
government. 
</P>
