<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Oil Firm to Enter Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Ring Oil International, a
French oil company, is going to invest 200 million U.S. Dollars
as a ticket to enter Nigeria, Africa's largest oil-producing
country.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said the money will be used as a "seed
fund" for Ring Oil's Nigerian affiliate, which intends to bid for
the planned upgrading of the Nigeria's ailing refinery industry.
</P>
<P>
Jeff Ike, the Managing Director of the company, said Ring Oil
also plans to establish a refinery plant in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He noted, however, the company's immediate focus will be the
purchasing and selling of Nigeria's crude oil, oil lifting,
production of artificial synthetic fibers and chemicals like
methanol.
</P>
<P>
It plans to be involved in the prospecting and production of
oil, said Ike, adding that his company is also interested in
acquiring part of the Nigerian government's interest in existing
oil producing joint ventures when it eventually decides to sell
the equity holdings.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is a member of the Organization of Petroleum Export
Countries (OPEC) and the largest oil-producing country in Africa.
At present, it produces about two million barrels of crude oil
daily.
</P>
<P>
The government has the monopoly over the petroleum industry
through the state-run Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation
(NNPC). Foreign oil firms can only operate in Nigeria through
joint ventures with the NNPC.
</P>
<P>
Ring Oil will be the seventh foreign oil firm to operate in
Nigeria, after Mobil, Shell, Cheveron, Agip, Texaco and Elf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
