<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Reform Military Commanding System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 11 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise today announced a plan to reorganize and
restructure the military at its top administrative levels.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming reform will include transferring of military
commanders and creating a new Ministry of Defense, Modise was
quoted by the South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils said the
military reform will create a mechanism that the secretary for
defense and the chief of the National Defense Force would operate
at the same hierarchical level under the Defense Minister.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary will play a role of departmental policy
adviser and the chief of armed forces will serve as departmental
military adviser.
</P>
<P>
Kasrils said the military reform is aimed at creating a more
effective and streamlined head office as well as saving 66
million U.S. Dollars of military budget.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the local press quoted Reg Otto, chief of the South
African Army, as saying that the armed forces in the country
would drastically disband and amalgamate its units as part of a
cost-saving exercise in the military services.
</P>
<P>
The downsizing of the armed forces would allow the army to
comply with budgetary restrictions while maintaining and
promoting combat efficiency, Otto said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
