<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Flower Exporters Complain about Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- High freight costs, now
representing 50 percent of input costs of Zimbabwe's flower
growers, are eroding the viability of the industry, exporters
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Mary Dunphy, administrator of the Export Flower Growers
Association of Zimbabwe, said freight costs varied from airline
to airline and prices per km ranged between 21 to 23 U.S. Cents.
</P>
<P>
"This is a high rate bearing in mind that for some flowers,
this will constitute 50 percent of the input costs. So we would
like to get that price lower," she said.
</P>
<P>
She added the harsh winter in Europe had also affected
business, and flower exports were reduced.
</P>
<P>
The association, which exports 70 percent of its products to
Europe and to the auction floors in the Netherlands, last year
exported 12,800 tons of flower worth about 39.3 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 16,000 tons of export was expected this year, she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
