<HEADLINE> Namibia, Germany to Start Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Namibia and Germany have
agreed to start military cooperation in the technical field.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers of the two countries have agreed to work
out a memorandum of understanding, to be signed in Germany later
this year, the Southern African Broadcasting Association reported
today from Windhoek, capital of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
German Defense Minister Volker Ruhe, who had just concluded a
short visit to Windhoek, said on Monday that he looked forward to
developing military relations with Namibia.
</P>
<P>
He told the press in Windhoek that Namibian Defense Minister
Phillemon Malima will visit Germany to sign the proposed
memorandum once it is prepared.
</P>
<P>
Malima said Ruhe's visit has strengthened the already existing
relations and good cooperation between Germany and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's armed forces have received technical and material
assistance from Germany, worth more than 30 million U.S. Dollars,
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Seven senior army officers of Namibia, which won independence
in 1990, are undergoing specialized military training in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Namibia was declared a German protectorate in 1884 and
entrusted to South Africa in 1919 by the then League of Nations
following the outbreak of the First World War in 1914. 
</P>
</TEXT>
