<HEADLINE> Biko's Family Oppose Amnesty on His Murderer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The family of South
Africa's slain anti-apartheid activist, Steve Biko, is to take
legal action to oppose an amnesty bid by policemen involved in
his murder.
</P>
<P>
Biko's son, Nkosinathi Biko, told reporters here today that
the family remains opposed to any application for pardon on
persons who were responsible for killing his father.
</P>
<P>
The Bikos have instructed their lawyers to oppose the
applications.
</P>
<P>
Biko, leader of the Black Consciousness Movement of South
Africa, died of brain damage in police detention in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Five white police officers have applied to South Africa's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission for amnesty in return for
full confession about their roles in Biko's assassination.
</P>
<P>
The commission has the power to pardon people who confess to
crimes committed in the name of the apartheid system or its
opponents. 
</P>
