<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most German Firms Ready for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn, February 11 (Xinhua) -- About 72 percent of German firms
believe they are ready for the scheduled use in 1999 of Europe's
future single currency, the euro, showed results of a study
published today.
</P>
<P>
This is compared with an average of 49 percent for firms in the
five largest members of the European Union (EU) -- Germany,
France, Britain, Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
According to the study conducted by the polling institute
Market &AMP; Opinion Research International in November, Spanish firms
are second best prepared for the euro, with 58 percent giving
positive response.
</P>
<P>
British companies come third with a 45 percent response,
followed by 37 percent in Italy and 36 percent in France.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered 335 businesses in the five countries, 200 of
them top companies.
</P>
<P>
The results, issued in Stuttgart, seat of IBM Germany's
operations, said 77 percent of big German companies were
discussing the euro question with their banks, as against 55
percent in France, 53 percent in Britain, 28 percent in Spain and
27 percent in Italy.
</P>
<P>
It is also found that, however, only 38 percent of
smaller-sized businesses in the five countries felt they were
ready for the euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Life Responsible for Sexual Problems of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Modern life and inadequate or
incorrect information are largely responsible for the sexual
problems of Greeks, according to the findings of a recent
epidemiological study presented today by the Hellenic Sexology
Association.
</P>
<P>
The findings were presented prior to the first conference to
be held in Greece on contemporary sexology issues.
</P>
<P>
According to the study carried out by the Institute of Sexology
and Patras University, one in 10 Greeks has a sex problem, 60
percent of which concern premature ejaculation while 40 percent
are erection-related.
</P>
<P>
The picture is even gloomier when it comes to women, since it
is estimated that one in four fail to attain sexual satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of women fail to reach orgasm, while many
women report diminished sexual desire.
</P>
<P>
According to Salonika University professor of obstetrics and
gynaecology Z. Papathanasiou, the causes of most of the problems
in men and women are psychological.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the low birth rate in Greece, Gynaecologist M.
Kardamakis said that 20 percent of men over the age of 35 do
not want children, while two out of 10 couples living in cities
want but are unable to have children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Factory Gate Prices Reach 10-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Output prices of manufactured
goods in Britain rose only by 0.2 percent in January, giving a
year-on-year rise of 1.5 percent, the lowest level since October
1986, official figures showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said that the figures,
much better than the increase of about 0.5 percent expected by the
City, suggest there is little inflation pressure on the industrial
front at present and reinforced Chancellor of the Exchequer
Kenneth Clarke's decision not to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Input prices, or the costs of fuel and raw materials, fell 0.5
percent between December and January, leaving prices 6.2 percent
lower than a year ago, also a 10-year low, due largely to the
strength of the pound.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that two of the largest contributors to the fall
in import prices were imported metals, the price of which fell
almost 15 percent in the past year, and pulp and waste paper
prices, which dropped by 42.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
