<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Airways Celebrates With Record Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- British Airways reported record
pre-tax profits for the nine months to December as it started
celebrations to mark the 10th anniversary of its privatization
today.
</P>
<P>
At 933 million US dollars, pre-tax profits were 9.2 percent
higher than the comparable period last year and took the
post-privatization total to 5.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
To celebrate the occasion, the airline today offered a 16 US
dollar return fare on 10 seats on every Concorde flight for a
period of 10 days. The usual fare is 8,640 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
British Airways shares, brought by the public when Lord King
was chairman at 200 cents in an offer which was 11 times
oversubscribed, began trading on the Stock Exchange 10 years ago
today, leaping to an instant premium of 85 cents.
</P>
<P>
Since then the shareholder register has been reduced from 1.1
million to 235,000, but those investors who have stayed the course
have seen a minimum investment of a 400 US dollar increase in
value to 2,048 US dollars, including dividends.
</P>
<P>
Colin Marshall, chairman of the airline, said the airline was
on course to achieve its target of 1.6 billion US dollars worth of
savings over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
Robert Ayling, chief executive, refused to discuss details
about the size of the savings but promised more details with the
full-year figures in May.
</P>
<P>
Since privatization, British Airways revenues have topped 8
billion US dollars while the company has paid out more than 960
million US dollars in tax and 1,280 million US dollars in
dividends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
