<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeological Sites in Salonika to Be Shown on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Salonika, the second largest
city in northern Greece which has been declared cultural capital
of Europe this year, will have its long history of civilization
shown on specially drawn-up maps by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The city's cultural capital organization has prepared an
ambitious program to locate, study, record and display dozens of
archeological sites buried under that northern port city.
</P>
<P>
The program, entitled "the city under the city," will be
carried out with the cooperation of the three antiquities
departments responsible for ancient, Byzantine and historical
monuments and be completed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
At an estimated cost of over 500 million drachmas (208 million
U.S. dollars), part of which is hoped to be secured from European
Union funds, the program will divide Salonika according to
historical periods.
</P>
<P>
Special maps will be drawn up for each period, resulting in an
archeological atlas of the city.
</P>
<P>
Although no real excavation work will be carried out, Roman and
Byzantine monuments, walls and churches will be "revealed" through
scientific research, drawings and models.
</P>
<P>
"Our target is during 1997 to present, with adequate
documentation, about one-fifth of Salonkia's historical center,"
the art director of the cultural capital organization, Panos
Theodoridis, told a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
The aim is in essence an educational program, he said, adding
that it is also to "link up the existing and visible with that
which has disappeared."
</P>
<P>
The results of the program will be published in volumes and be
made available in electronic form. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-11 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Amir's Former girlfriend Indicted for Assisting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Margalit Har-Shefi, former
girlfriend of Yigal Amir who assassinated former Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, was indicted today for abetting Amir in
the murder.
</P>
<P>
The indictment, which was filed in Tel Aviv Magistrate's
Court, charged Har-Shefi with failing to prevent Rabin's murder
and giving Amir the means of committing crimes.
</P>
<P>
Amir shot with a pistol and killed Rabin on November 4, 1995,
after the former premier attended a mass peace rally in Tel
Aviv. He is now serving life sentence after being convicted of
murder.
</P>
<P>
According to the indictment, Har-Shefi knew about Amir's plan
to murder Rabin but failed to notify proper authorities; and she
also provided Amir with information on committing anti-Arab
activities.
</P>
<P>
Har-Shefi, a 20-year-old student from Beit El, was detained
two days after Rabin's assassination, but was released after 17
days later.
</P>
<P>
She admitted having heard about Amir's plan to assassinate
Rabin, but argued that she doubted that he would really commit
it.
</P>
<P>
If convicted of the two accounts of crimes, Har-Shefi will
face up to five years in jail. Today's charge came following the
State Attorney's Office's decision Monday to indict her.
</P>
<P>
Har-Shefi's indictment was filed 15 months after Rabin's
murder. The Justice Ministry explained that the delay was due to
two reasons: Har-Shefi was a witness in the conspiracy trial of
Amir and his brother Haggai, and the State Attorney's Office did
not want her testimony to be compromised.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, because six people were being investigated on
similar charges, the investigation involved a lengthy amount of
cross-checking.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the five other people investigated have been
cleared of charges of conspiracy in the Rabin's murder due to
insufficient evidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
