<HEADLINE> UK Parliament on IRA Bomb Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Security measures at
Westminster have been tightened after a warning that the Houses of
Parliament could be the target of the IRA attack.
</P>
<P>
It was officially announced that from Wednesday, entry into the
Houses of Parliament on foot is to be severely restricted.
</P>
<P>
Commons pass-holders also face spot checks and bag searches
because security chiefs fear there are IRA "sleepers" in the
building.
</P>
<P>
"They are worried about the enemy within -- people working at
the Commons whom nobody has suspected," said a senior government
official.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions are being imposed after an MI5 warning that
IRA terrorists are monitoring the comings and goings at the
Commons and continue to view MPs and Parliament as possible
targets.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to all Commons staff, MI5 said security
measures were being introduced or reinforced because the building
remained at a high level of threat from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Although there is understood to be no specific threat to
Westminster, security chiefs regard the run-up to the election as
a highly sensitive time in which the IRA might be tempted to mount
an attack.
</P>
<P>
At the weekend the IRA leadership said it was "highly unlikely"
there would be a fresh cease-fire in the run-up to the election,
and denied that it was engaged in a phoney war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
