<HEADLINE> Europe Takes Lion's Share in Egypt's Tourist Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Up to 23 million European
tourists spent their holidays in Egypt last year, placing Europe
at the top of tourist-exporting continents to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency today quoted Minister of Tourism
Mamdouh el-Beltagui as saying that European tourists spent almost
14 million nights in Egypt in 1996, an increase of 33 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Germany, topping the European countries, provided Egypt with
altogether 321,000 tourists to Egypt in 1996, an 8 percent rise
over 1995.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by Italy, England and Israel, which comes
fourth with 321,000, an increase of 8 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
France ranked fifth with 242,000 tourists, which doubled the
number of 1995, he added.
</P>
<P>
Up to 217,000 tourists arrived from Saudi Arabia, a rise of 20
percent over 1995, placing the kingdom on the sixth among
tourist-exporting countries to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. came in seventh, contributing 175,000 tourists to
Egypt, registering a 13 percent increase over 1995, Beltagui said.
</P>
<P>
Benelux countries provided Egypt with 133,000 tourists,
representing a 58 percent increase over 1995, and ranking eighth,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Russia ranked ninth, with 125,000 tourists and Switzerland
10th with 99,000 tourists, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
