<HEADLINE> Mozambique Has Good Harvest Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique scored a good
harvest in the 1995/96 agricultural year by producing 1.38
million tons of grain in total, which was up by 22 percent than
the 1.12 million tons in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed today by Mozambican Minister of Agriculture
and Fishery Carlos Do Rosario who was speaking at a meeting of
the Council of Coordination of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to a document presented to the meeting by the
minister, the output of earthnuts and cassava also increased
sharply.
</P>
<P>
During the 1995/96 agricultural year, 120,000 tons of
earthnuts was harvested in the country, representing an increase
of 20,000 tons than the previous year, while the production of
cassava was increased to 4.73 million tons from the previous
year's 4.17 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Among exportable cash crops, the output of raw cashew was
increased to 66,510 tons in the year of 1995/96 at a rate of 99
percent, and that of cashew nuts increased to 4,029 tons from the
previous year's 3139 tons.
</P>
<P>
However, Mozambique also experienced failure in cotton,
orange, tobacco and other crops, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, being held in southern Mozambique, will close on
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
