<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Capital Successfully Controls Spread of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of cholera
victims who were admitted in hospital in the Tanzanian capital
Dar es Salaam has decreased from 17 to six by today, indicating
successful control of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Dar es Salaam City Commission (DCC) Commissioner for Health
Matiku Nyakarungu told reporters here today that four patients
are remaining at Amana Hospital and two others were at the newly
established Cholera Emergency Center at Kipawa area in the city.
</P>
<P>
"Three of them could be discharged at any time from now
because their condition has highly improved. They are only
waiting for final results," he said.
</P>
<P>
The DCC commissioner for health said the newly cholera
emergency center established at the most affected area of Kipawa
last Saturday has contributed greatly in controlling the disease.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, health officers also conducted mass
education to the public over the epidemic and distributed
essential drugs from house to house in the city.
</P>
<P>
However, Nyakarungu cautioned city residents to keep their
premises clean, boil drinking water, eat hot food and wash fruits
with clean water before eating.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if health rules are not observed, heavy loss of
human lives is likely to occur with the approaching rains as
floods will spread the germs "vibrio choleras".
</P>
<P>
Cholera erupted on January 19 in Kipawa and Buguruni areas in
the city, whereby 17 out of the 32 people who were suffering from
diarrhoea were diagnosed cholera positive and admitted in
hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
