<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Countries Want UNEP to Be "Exclusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 11 (Xinhua) -- An Indian official has said
that some developed countries aimed at turning the U.N.
Environmental Program (UNEP) into an "exclusive club" at the
just-suspended 19th session of the UNEP Governing Council.
</P>
<P>
In an article issued here today, Indian High Commissioner to
Kenya T.P.L. Screenivasan noted that the controversy during the
session was about the merits of an existing democratic system of
governance as against an exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
Since the last session, developed countries have been calling
for a review of the UNEP governing structure while drastically
reducing their contributions to the UNEP, said the Indian
official who is one of the vice-presidents of the UNEP Governing
Council meeting opened on January 27.
</P>
<P>
At the insistence of some developed countries, UNEP Executive
Director Elizabeth Dowdeswell proposed the creation of an
Executive Board to implement decisions adopted by the Governing
Council.
</P>
<P>
But, Screenivasan pointed out, the proposal was unanimously
rejected by the developing countries because it struck at the
very root of democratic decision making system at the Governing
Council.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the set-up of a small Executive Board as an
inter-sessional body would deprive the great numbers of the
Governing Council members of the opportunity to have their say in
the UNEP administration.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from the West major donors, the developing
countries have agreed in principles to establish a high level
committee if it is open to all member countries, said
Screenivasan who is chairman of the Committee of Permanent
Representatives to the UNEP.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, one concession on the part of the
developing countries led to a demand to set up another group for
reform to manage UNEP affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Indian official pointed out that the message from the 19th
session was that the UNEP would be reshaped by the powerful
nations in accordance with their own vision and priorities.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, he called on developing countries to take
united actions to ensure that the UNEP remains relevant to the
environmental needs of the whole world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
