<HEADLINE> UN Security Council Condemns Killing in Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today strongly condemned the killing of a
civilian in the divided Bosnian town of Mostar earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued at the end of the consultations of the
15-member council said that all the member states of the council
"condemned in the strongest possible term the discriminative
killing of one civilian in Mostar today."
</P>
<P>
The council demanded that "those responsible for the acts be
identified, be arrested and brought to trial," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on all responsible citizens in Mostar
to "remain calm and maintain peace."
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the members of the Security Council would
continue to follow closely development of the situation in Mostar.
</P>
<P>
The incident came only one day after Bosnian Croats reportedly
opened fire on a crowd of Moslems visiting a cemetery in Mostar
Monday. At least four people were wounded, an international police
spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The shooting and killing followed rising tensions over the
past month in Mostar between Moslem and Croat communities.
</P>
<P>
The violence has coincided with political battles inside the
Moslem-Croat federation over power-sharing and budgets.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Moslems and Croats fought a vicious 10-month war in
1993-94 until they agreed to form the federation under heavy U.S.
pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
