<HEADLINE> Canada to Defend Culture Against US Incursions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada will use every weapon in
its arsenal to fight U.S. assaults on its cultural policy, said
Heritage Minister Sheila Copps.
</P>
<P>
"If the Americans want to enter a good dialogue on good policy,
we're prepared to do it," Copps said at the end of the country's
two-day culture summit here.
</P>
<P>
"But don't lecture the most open market for cultural products
in the world with the kind of one-way denunciations that we've
seen emanating from the U.S. trade representative," she warned.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government "is prepared to use all the tools in
our arsenal to fight decisions that restrict our capacity to build
our own culture," the minister vowed.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans are playing hardball on the issue of the (World
Trade Organization) and magazine. Well, we can play hardball too,"
she was quoted as saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
The summit was designed to review existing policies and new
ways to protect its culture when the U.S. is mounting bigger
efforts to crack open the border for its cultural products.
</P>
<P>
The meeting became all the more urgent to the Canadian cultural
industries, after the WTO ruled last month that Canada should
change its policies protecting the domestic magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government will appeal the WTO ruling, Copps told
the meeting of country's largest cultural industries and
institutions.
</P>
<P>
She also revealed that the government "is looking at whether
there are other instruments we can use to protect our magazine
industry."
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, next week's federal budget will
include a 7.4 million U.S. dollar broadcast fund for CBC radio
and a loan guarantee program for Canadian book publishers.
</P>
</TEXT>
