<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Population Grows in 1996 to 58.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The population in mainland
France stood at 58.5 million on January 1, 1997, and the number of
new-born babies increased by 1 percent that year, while that of
newly-married couples rose by 10 percent, said a demographic study
by the official statistics bureau INSEE today.
</P>
<P>
The number of people in France increased by 238,000 in 1996,
including a natural increase of 198,000 and 40,000 immigrants,
while 734,000 babies were born in France in the year, said the
survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the average number of children born by a
French woman stood at 1.72 in 1996, as is compared with 1.7 in
1995 and 1.65 in 1993 and 1994, and is higher than 1.43 in average
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The average age for French women to give birth to their
children was 29 in 1995, as is compared with 27 in 1981, it said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who died in France in 1996 stood at
536,000, 4,000 more than 1995.
</P>
<P>
The average life expectancy in France is 74 years for man and
82 for women, which represents the largest gap of life expectancy
between the two sexes in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Some 279,000 couples got married in 1996, a 10 percent increase
over 1995 and the highest rise since early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 24 percent of French women above 35 remained
unmarried in 1995, and 38 percent of the new born babies in 1995
came to a single mother family, as is compared with 10 percent in
1979.
</P>
<P>
The number of immigrants, which stood at 40,000 in 1995 and
1996, has dropped from 90,000 in 1991 and 1992, 70,000 in 1993 and
50,000 in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
