<HEADLINE> Most European Shares End Slightly Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock markets in London and
Paris all closed a lackluster session in the negative ground
Tuesday, with Frankfurt the only exception and closing slightly
higher.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE index on the London market ended 3.4 points down at
4,304.3, depressed by Wall Street's overnight fall.
</P>
<P>
Some disappointing corporate results dominated the day as did
sterling's four year high against the German mark, which made
traders concerned about its effect on exports.
</P>
<P>
French stocks also finished slightly lower, dragged down by
profit-taking and overnight falls on Wall Street, but firm bonds
and the stronger dollar tempered losses, with the CAC-40 index
13.28 points down at 2,582.09.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares posted slim gains with support
coming from bond prices and the strong dollar, which was
favorable for German exports, with the DAX-30 index 3.22 points
up at 3,187.58.
</P>
<P>
Dealers remained upbeat about the chances of the DAX-30 index
breaching the 3,200 level this week.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended down
3.4 points at 4,304.3. The Paris CAC-40 index finished 13.28
points down at 2,582.09. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index closed up 3.22
points at 3,187.58. 
