<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has revived an offer to international firms to
set up an export-oriented oil refinery in its Red Sea port of
Aqaba, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Ministry was seeking international bidders by April
30 to construct, operate and own the projected plant, whose
capacity is designed to be 210,000 barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed an initial agreement with corporate Holdings of
America Inc (CHA) for a similar refinery last year. Under the
agreement, CHA wold have handed the refinery over to Jordan after
20 years of operation.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- An investment firm has asked for permission from
Kuwait's Central Bank to set up the country's first Islamic bank,
Al-Qabas daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Sami al-Bader, executive President of the International
Investment Group, said the capital of the proposed bank would be
about 50 million dinars (166.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has one Islamic banking institution, the Kuwait Finance
House, but it is not registered as a bank. Islamic banking is
based on profit-sharing rather than interest.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will build a 250-kilometer power cable that will
connect the Sinai resorts of Taba and Sharm al-Sheik, Arabic
language newspaper al-Akhbar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 22 million dollars and should be
completed by December. The cable, to be built with the help of
German and Turkish teams, will help ensure steady electricity to
Sharm al-Sheik, a booming resort on the Sinai Peninsula's southern
tip.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Koor Industries Ltd., Israeli largest industrial
concern, will send a delegation on an investors' road show to one
of the Gulf states later this year following Israel's improved
relations with neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Jerusalem Post published today,
Koor's Chief Executive Officer (CEO) Benjamin Gaon  offered a
broad assessment of the relationship between big business and the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Gaon, who would not specify exactly when the event will take
place or in which country, said the plan reflects improvement in
Israeli business relations with neighboring countries following
the Hebron agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
