<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Lakes' Water Levels Could Drop Drastically, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Rising consumption and the
effects of global warming could cause a reduction of over 25
percent in the amount of water flowing out of the Great Lakes,
according to a new study by two environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
The drop would occur over 40 years if no actions are taken to
make farmers, businesses and consumers rethink their "outrageous"
use of water of the lakes.
</P>
<P>
They could drop even further if major diversion projects are
approved to move water from the Great Lakes to parched areas of
the United States, the report warned.
</P>
<P>
North America's Great Lakes are the largest freshwater system
in the world, containing 23,000 cubic kilometres of water. Some 33
million people live around or near the lakes.
</P>
<P>
A major drop in Great Lakes water levels could harm animals,
lake freighters and hydroelectric stations, said the report by
Great Lakes United and the Canadian Environmental Law Association.
</P>
<P>
Drastically lower levels would also dry up wetlands used by
waterfowl, change beaches and decrease shorefront property values,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"If we allow these changes to occur, the Great Lakes area will
be a very different place from the home that we now live in. Our
health, our cultures and our economies will all be substantially
changed," it said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that per capita water consumption in the United States
and Canada is the highest in the world, the report called for a
50-percent cut in water use by 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
