<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's Public Deficit Drops 28 Bln Francs in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- France's public deficit dropped
by 28 billion francs (5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 to stay at
295 billion francs (53 billion U.S. dollars), Minister of Economy
and Finance Jean Arthuis announced today.
</P>
<P>
The figures represent 4.1 percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP) of France, higher than 3 percent of GDP as is required by
the Maastricht Treaty signed by the European Union (EU) countries
for joining the single European currency euro.
</P>
<P>
France has to further lower its public deficit to 3 percent
this year to join the euro in the first wave, scheduled for
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac today congratulated the
government on having controlled public spending over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
He called for further cutting of public spending, which
includes spending by the state, by the social security system, and
by local communities.
</P>
<P>
Althuis said that the increase of public spending in 1996 over
1995 stood at 1.7 percent, for the first time below the country's
inflation rate, which stood at 2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the public debt of France continued to grow
in 1996, and said that France has to cut its public deficit to 2
percent of GDP to decrease its public debt. 
</P>
