<HEADLINE> Japan's PM Apologizes Over Radioactive Bullets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today apologized to the Okinawa prefectural government
over belated notification about radioactive bullets fired by
United States Marines a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the apology at a session of the House of
Representatives Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Marine Corp. jets fired a total of 1,520 radioactive
bullets on Torishima Island off Okinawa during training exercises
in December,1995 and January,1996. Washington informed the
Japanese foreign ministry of the incident last month.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. Marine regulations, the use of radioactive bullets
is prohibited in any places in Japan, including the uninhabited
island of Torishima.
</P>
<P>
The belated notification prompted Okinawa Governor Masahide
Ota, an outspoken critic of the U.S. military presence in the
prefecture, to fiercely criticize the U.S. military and the
Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
At the lower house session, Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda
acknowledged that the government had neglected the impact of the
incident on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, about 1,600 kilometers southwest of Tokyo, accounts
for only 0.6 percent of the country's total land area while
accommodating 75 percent of the U.S. military presence in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
