<HEADLINE>   EU Prohibits Pig Exports From Six German States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
approved a ban Tuesday on the export of pigs from six German
states to counter an outbreak of swine fever.
</P>
<P>
The ban, which went into effect immediately, prohibits for at
least 60 days the export of live pigs from Mecklenburg-Western
Pomerania, Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, Bavaria, Bremen
and two districts of Brandenburg.
</P>
<P>
According to an EU spokesman, the ban would be lifted after 60
days unless fresh outbreaks of the fever occurred.
</P>
<P>
Hungary decided to suspend imports of pigs from Germany
Tuesday. And the EC reportedly considered action to curb the
outbreak of the disease in the Netherlands today.
</P>
<P>
Swine fever is a highly contagious and fatal disease which
affects pigs. 
</P>
