<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Spends More on Crude Oil Imports in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's petroleum import
expenditure soared by 28.5 percent in 1996 due to higher oil
prices on the world markets, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Frankfurt-based Federal Economic Office,
Germany imported 102.9 million tons of crude oil in 1996, an
increase of only 2.2 percent over 1995, but that volume cost 23.9
billion marks (about 15.9 billion U.S. dollars), an increase of
28.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Russia surpassed Norway as Germany's top oil supplier for the
first time in 1996, with the export of 26 million tons as against
22 million tons from Norway.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Libya and Saudi Arabia were the third, fourth and
fifth largest oil suppliers for Germany in 1996 with deliveries of
18 million, 12 million and six million tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Germany got 39 percent of its crude
oil from North Sea suppliers and about 30 percent from countries
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
