<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Launches Rockets with Radio Telescope Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan launched a new rocket
today carrying the world's first radio telescope satellite into
space, said the Education Ministry's Institute of Space and
Astronautical Science.
</P>
<P>
Minutes after the lift-off from a launch in the town of
Uchinoura, Kagoshima Prefecture, southwestern Japan, the 830
kilogram Muse-B satellite separated from the rocket and was put
into elliptical orbit around the Earth.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will link up with ground-based telescopes to
probe major sources in the galaxy, such as distant quasars and
black holes.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, which uses radio astronomy technology, has a
life expectancy of at least three years.
</P>
<P>
It was placed in orbit with an apogee height of 20,000
kilometers and a perigee height of 1,000 km to observe radio
sources such as quasars and masers in cooperation with radio
telescopes on Earth, over a period of three to five years.
</P>
<P>
The satellite's magnifying power for celestial bodies is
equivalent to being able to see from Tokyo a grain of rice in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The M-5 rocket is the fifth generation of M-series rockets. The
30-meter, three-stage rocket, developed by the institute, is
capable of launching a satellite weighing up to 1.8 tons.
</P>
<P>
The rocket was designed to match increasing demands for larger
payload capacities and is powerful enought for missions to Mars,
Venus and outlying asteroids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
