<HEADLINE> Yunnan Makes Marked Economic Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan, a multi-ethnic
province in southwest China, recorded all-round economic
development last year.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of the province registered a
10-percent rise, and the grain output was a historical high in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of industry increased by 15.4 percent last
year, 2.4 percent higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
In addition, last year the province invested 12 billion yuan in
basic industry. The 13 key projects listed by the local government
have all been completed.
</P>
<P>
The first expressway in the province has been completed and a
complete railway network has been formed. Construction of the
railway trunk between the provincial capital of Kunming and
Nanning, in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, is nearing
completion.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's power generating capacity has grown by 300,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
The four pillar industries of Yunnan, including minerals and
tourism, turned over to the state 50 billion yuan in taxes and
profits last year.
</P>
<P>
The local government earmarked 1.3 billion yuan for getting 1.2
million poor people out of poverty and allocated another one
billion yuan for helping people in disaster-stricken areas to
rebuild their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
