<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Questions US Security Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Maintaining United States
national security does not necessarily require interference in the
legitimate trade between European companies and Cuba, European
Union Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan said today.
</P>
<P>
Brittan made the remarks in a statement which aims to give the
U.S. more timed to reach an agreed settlement with the European
Union (EU) on the disputed Helms-Burton and D'Amato Acts before
the World Trade Organization (WTO) forms a panel to resolve the
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Any resort to arguments of national security in a WTO dispute
settlement procedure must clearly be related to genuine national
security concerns," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was impossible for a country to evade the WTO
settlement procedure simply by proclaiming that its national
security was involved.
</P>
<P>
He said no country would be allowed to be judge or jury "in its
own cause" to damage the WTO dispute settlement procedure.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said the essence of an independent dispute settlement
mechanism was that no country could expect to win every
case. Instead, all countries accepted that the gains in having
such a system far outweighed the risks of losing particular cases.
</P>
<P>
"We have no desire to take our case to the point of decision by
a panel for its own sake," he said. The EU's concern was to
protect legitimate European trade interests which had been damaged
by the U.S. extraterritorial bills.
</P>
<P>
Brittan today asked WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero to
postpone the nomination of the panel by one week, until February
20, the deadline for the panel's nomination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serious Faction Fighting Erupts in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 12 (Xinhua) -- At least five people were
killed and 12 others wounded in a heavy fighting this
morning in North Mogadishu, Somalia, according to eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which erupted in Shebbis District between forces
loyal to the Islamic leader, Sheikh Ali Sheikh Mohamud, and those
supporting the rival North Mogadishu faction leader, Ali Mahdi
Mohamed, was the most serious armed clash in North Mogadishu
since last October.
</P>
<P>
Local people said the rival militiamen used technical
vehicles, anti-tank guns, mortar rounds and heavy machine guns
during the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Although the spokesman for Sheikh Ali denied that the fighting
took place between Sheikh Ali's forces and the men loyal to Ali
Mahdi, he characterized the fight as a war between the Islamic
militiamen and what he called gunmen against the pacification of
North Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
So far there is no word yet from Ali Mahdi's side on the
fighting. However, the roads leading to the main Islamic court
have been cut off.
</P>
<P>
The North Mogadishu people had been enjoying peace since the
Islamic courts were established in the region two years ago.
</P>
<P>
But the security in North Mogadishu has deteriorated in
October last year when Ali Mahdi issued a decree which removed
Sheikh Ali from his chairmanship of the High Islamic court.
Sheikh Ali denounced the decree.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Mogadishu controlled by Ali Mahdi's main
rival, Hussein Mohamed Aidid, has remained calm.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Guiseppe Cassini, a special envoy from
the Italian government, met on Tuesday with Ali Mahdi in a bid to
bring the North Mogadishu faction leader to peace talks with
Hussein Aidid, the South Mogadishu warlord.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said a face-to-face negotiation, which would
soon be brought about in the neighboring Kenyan capital of
Nairobi, could start a new round of peace initiative in Somalia
which has been torn apart by six years of civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Garments Exports Surge in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' garments
export earnings hit 247.168 million US dollars in January, a 9.88
percent jump from 224.946 million US dollars in the same month
last year, data from the Philippine Garments and Textile Export
Board showed.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, the quota countries absorbed 79.23 percent or
195.840 million US dollars, reflecting a 7.96 percent increase
from 181.399 million US dollars in January 1996, the data showed.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, exports to the non-quota countries posted a
substantial 17.87 percent increase to 51.327 million US dollars
from 43.547 million US dollars during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the quota countries, exports to the United States
improved by 9.37 percent to 152.300 million US dollars from
139.253 million US dollars a year earlier. Shipments to the US
accounted for a 61.62 percent share of the total export.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the European Union inched up by 3.62 percent to
38.779 million US dollars from 37.377 million US dollars,
absorbing a 15.67 percent share of the total exports.
</P>
<P>
Canada, the third biggest quota country, registered a slight
increase of 0.89 percent to 4.81 million US dollars from 4.768
million US dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Among the non-quota countries, Japan topped the list with total
shipments valued at 13.6 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
