<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outward Processing in China's inland Contributes to HK Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Outward processing trade
accounted for half of Hong Kong's total exports to China's
interior areas in the third quarter of 1996, as shown by the
latest government statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, outward processing trade made up for 75
percent of Hong Kong's domestic exports and nearly 50 percent of
its re-exports, according to the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
Outward processing is a popular form of trade between Hong Kong
and booming towns in Southern China. Hong Kong first exports raw
materials or semi-manufactures to interior areas for processing,
and then imports the processed goods.
</P>
<P>
During the third quarter of 1996, Hong Kong exported more than
62 billion HK dollars (about eight billion US dollars) worth of
raw materials or semi-manufactures to interior areas for outward
processing, representing an increase of 11 percent over the same
period of 1995. The domestic exports to China's inland areas for
outward processing fell by six percent to some 11.5 billion HK
dollars (1.5 billion US dollars), while re-exports to the areas
for outward processing jumped by 15 percent to almost 50.6 billion
HK dollars (6.5 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, about 80 percent of Hong Kong's imports from
China's interior areas in the July-September period were related
to outward processing. During the period, the value of imports in
this category hit 336 billion HK dollars (43 billion US dollars),
up 13 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Out of Hong Kong's re-exports of China-made goods to other
countries, 86 percent were produced through outward processing in
the third quarter of 1996. The total value amounted to 410 billion
HK dollars (52.5 billion US dollars), up 14 percent from the same
quarter of 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
