<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Officials Visit Snowstorm-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Leading officials in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have braved winds and
snowstorms to visit farmers and herdsmen in snowstorm-hit areas
during the Spring Festival period.
</P>
<P>
Wang Lequan, secretary of the autonomous regional committee of
the Communist Part of China (CPC), and other ranking officials
drove over 1,000 miles to Altay Prefecture, a seriously affected
area, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the house of Murat Hadi, a herdsman living in the
snow-covered Gobi Desert, Wang asked Murat whether he could find
enough grass to feed his sheep.
</P>
<P>
Murat replied that he had used 7.5 tons of fodder so far but
what he had left may not cope with the need.
</P>
<P>
Wang told Murat he would discuss the matter with relevant
officials after he returned to the county seat and try to
get for him adequate fodder and daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Then the regional party secretary gave two bags of brick tea,
sugar and some cotton-padded clothes to the household and wished
all the family members a happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
Murat, moved to tears, expressed his gratitude to the Communist
Party of China and the People's Government.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, Wang and his party kept busy visiting a
number of families of ethnic Kazakh minority that is in need and
organizing local officials to fight the snowstorm disasters in the
past three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
