<HEADLINE> Russian Gas Exports to Double in 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian gas exports are
expected to almost double, from 197 billion cubic meters (bcm) in
1996 to 360 bcm in 2015, says a press release today by the United
Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UN/ECE).
</P>
<P>
The release was issued when the seventh session of the UN/ECE
working party on gas was held in Geneva last month.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the fall in economic activity in Russia, the gas
sector achieved good results in 1996, and its future now seems
more promising than ever," said the UN/ECE in its press release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the release said: "To sustain the predicted export
levels, considerable investments are required in the Russian gas
industry." It said there was a lack of financial resources.
</P>
<P>
According to the All-Russia Institute for Gas Problems, the
scientific and research arm of GAZPROM, Russia's biggest gas
corporation, Russia's production will rise to 929 bcm by 2015 from
current production of 600 bcm, an increase of 55 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
