<HEADLINE> Campaign to be Launched to Stop Military Exercise In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Environment and peace groups
in Australia will campaign to stop the joint US-Australian
military exercise "Tandem Thrust" to be held on the north
Queensland coast.
</P>
<P>
Plans for the operation were highlighted this week when a US
supply ship, USNS Kilauea was reported to have run out of fuel off
Townsville and a case of smoke grenades was lost into the sea.
</P>
<P>
Australian Anti-bases Campaign Coalition's national coordinator
Dennis Doherty said today that he would brief activists and launch
the "Stop Tandem Thrust" campaign in Brisbane tomorrow, according
to a press release available here.
</P>
<P>
He said the exercise, to be held in the Shoalwater Bay training
area near Rockhampton in March would involve 17,000 US and 5,000
Australian troops in one of the biggest peacetime exercises in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Doherty said peace and environment groups were opposed to the
war game because of the threats it poses to the environment and
because of its purpose which is to prepare for intervention in
countries that did not agree with US policies.
</P>
<P>
The threats included oil spills, toxic chemicals from live
ammunition and concerns about a nuclear accident (as a nuclear
submarine will be involved in the exercise) in the area which
would threaten the Great Barrier Reef and the habitats of dugongs
and green turtles.
</P>
<P>
People from Brisbane, Sydney, Rockhampton, Mackay, Yeppoon and
other areas would also protest against the military exercise,
according to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
