<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Issue Global Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today announced that the Philippine Central Bank will
formally launch 1 billion US dollar Global Bond issue in April.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Monetary Board has chosen Salomon Brothers as
the lead manager for this bond offering with JP Morgan, Citicorp,
Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley and ING-Baring as co-leads, a news
release from the Presidential Palace said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as
saying that with the US dollar interest rates at historic low
levels and with the current strong market demand for long-dated
debt securities, the bond issue is expected to be well-received
and priced at advantageous terms for the country.
</P>
<P>
Singson also said the Central Bank Global Bond will be the
first non-investment grade paper to be issued that will carry very
long dated tenors.
</P>
<P>
The bond will have a target maturity of a minimum of 30 years
and possibly, where market demand is determined to be sufficient
just prior to launch, a 100 years maturity.
</P>
<P>
Singson explained that the Central Bank is the only Philippine
public sector entity that can issue such very long-dated tenors as
the country's own issuance is limited by law to a maximum of 25
years.
</P>
<P>
The Global Bond, Singson added, is envisioned to establish a
long-dated benchmark for Philippine borrowers, highlighting the
strong performance of the economy and market acceptance of the
Philippine credit.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds from the bond offering will be used principally to
build up the country's international reserves which is presently
at around 11.4 billion US dollars, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
