<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Funds for Three Gorges Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 2.8 billion
yuan this year for the resettlement of people who are living in
and near the Three Gorges Dam Project, in central China's Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
The funds will mainly be used for relocating people in the
flooded areas when the Yangtze River is dammed in November this
year and for the emergency excavation of cultural relics in the
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1.2 million people are expected to move out of areas
affected by the gigantic dam project, believed to be the largest
of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale evacuation began in 1993, after an eight-year
relocation on an experimental basis. The state has earmarked 5.8
billion yuan for the resettlement of evacuees in the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
Calculated on the basis of May 1993 prices, the relocation will
cost 40 billion yuan. But officials in charge of the resettlement
predict that more money will be allocated for the scheme in
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
