<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Bars Germany Meeting EMU Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany could not meet the
standards for the 1999 European Monetary Union (EMU) set by the
Maastricht Treaty because of the record high unemployment rate, a
German economist said today.
</P>
<P>
Klaus-Werner Schatz, vice president of the Kiel International
Economic Research Institute, told the Flensburger Tageblatt
newspaper that the rising unemployment was likely to result in a
60 billion marks deficit this year, higher than the expected 50
billion.
</P>
<P>
Schatz said the deficits could account for 3.4 percent of the
gross domestic product, which meant Germany could not meet the EMU
criteria.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the time for achieving a single currency
system be postponed, so strengthening the reliability of the
monetary union.
</P>
<P>
The number of unemployed in Germany soared to nearly 4.66
million in January, the highest since 1933, official statistics
showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
