<HEADLINE> Ties With Singapore Remarkable, Says British FS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said here today that his country enjoys
"a remarkable relationship" with Singapore, but there remain
opportunities to seize.
</P>
<P>
"In almost every sphere of life, Britain and Singapore work
closely together," Rifkind noted in a speech to the Institute of
Policy Studies here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that business is "the heart of our relationship,"
citing a two-way trade volume of 6.7 billion U.S. dollars for
1995.
</P>
<P>
Rifkind expressed his country's welcome to Singaporean
investment in Britain, which is the fourth largest foreign
investor in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, Rifkind met with his Singaporean
counterpart, S. Jayakumar and the two men had "a wide-ranging
discussion on Singapore-U.K. bilateral relations, the forthcoming
ASEAN-EU Ministerial Meeting and ASEM Foreign Ministers Meeting in
Singapore and regional and international developments," according
to a Singaporean Foreign Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The two officials also had "a fruitful discussion on the Action
Agenda on Singapore-U.K. Relations," which will serve as the
framework for the continued growth and development of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed a new agreement for the avoidance
of double taxation to replace an old one signed in 1966.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary arrived here this morning for a
visit to Singapore before attending the two-day 12th ASEAN-EU
Ministerial Meeting which will start tomorrow and the ASEM Foreign
Ministers' Meeting to be held on February 15.  
</P>
