<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Home Minister Resigns Over Hanbo Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Home Minister Kim
Woo-suk, involved in the Hanbo loan scandal, has offered to
resign, a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who is being investigated for bribery in connection with
the Hanbo scandal, telephoned Prime Minister Lee Soo-sung this
morning before his summons by the prosecution and offered his
resignation, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official said President Kim Young-sam would accept the
resignation and immediately appoint a successor.
</P>
<P>
He added that kim told the prime minister on the telephone that
he "is sorry for his involvement in the Hanbo loan scandal".
</P>
<P>
Kim Woo-suk, along with the ruling New Korea Party (NKP)
legislator Hwang Byung-tai and the opposition National Congress
for New Politics (NCNP) legislator Kwon Roh-kap, was summoned by
the prosecution today for questioning on suspected involvement in
the Hanbo loan scandal.
</P>
<P>
Kim is suspected of taking bribes from the Hanbo Business Group
in return for financial favors to Hanbo while serving as president
of the Korea Land Development Corporation in 1993, and as
construction and transportation minister in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution said Hanbo's Chairman, Chung Tae-soo, had
bribed some politicians with huge amounts of money in order to
finance his project of setting up a steel mill in the country's
South Chungchong Province.
</P>
<P>
Chung Tae-soo, who was arrested by the prosecution on January
31 on charges of fraud and embezzlement, allegedly secured six
billion U.S. dollars for his flagship firm, Hanbo Iron and Steel
Company. The company was declared bankrupt by its creditors on
January 23 after failing to honor billions of U.S. dollars in
notes.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam today ordered law enforcement
authorities to "strictly and fairly" investigate anyone involved
in the Hanbo loan scandal.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't know corruption and irregularities were so serious,"
Kim said, adding that there should be a thorough probe without
allowing any havens.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Lee Soo-sung said today that he would
take responsibility for the Hanbo loan scandal, hinting that he
might resign when the investigation finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
