<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Opts for No Dialog, Confrontation with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani said here today that Iran seeks neither dialogue, nor
confrontation with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question at a press conference, Rafsanjani said,
"There can be a third alternative to the dialogue and
confrontation" in Iran's policy to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"That is to be in the state of no war, and no peace as we are
in now," said the 62-year-old president.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Washington broke diplomatic ties shortly after
Iran's Islamic Revolution in 1979, which toppled the pro-U.S. Shah
Pahlavi, and the two countries have been hostile to each other
over almost all issues since then.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has imposed sanctions on Iran and even threatened the
Islamic state with a military strike against 19 targets,
including the alleged training camps for extremists and nuclear
reactors in the country.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said "I don't see any new threats against the
country from the United States and we would continue to pursue our
previous policy toward the United States."
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "Unofficially there are statements against
Iran via some media... to the friends of Iran and subsequent
threats of revenge."
</P>
<P>
But, Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei warned of the possible
danger and said late last month that Iran is ready to confront any
potential U.S. military strike against the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani criticized the U.S. for lack of goodwill in
relations with Iran, adding "If it begins to show goodwill it
would see a different face from Iran."
</P>
<P>
"One of the ways of showing their goodwill is to free Iranian
assets frozen by the United States. If they do that we would
interpret the gesture as a change of policy," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
