<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Optimism About Business Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Most industrialists are
optimistic about the general business situation for the next six
months ending June 1997, according to a survey of Business
Expectations of the Manufacturing Sector by the government's
Economic Development Board (EDB), which was released today.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the number of manufacturing
establishments that expect a positive business situation for the
next six months outweigh those that are pessimistic by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The more optimistic industries are the electronics, chemical
products, transport equipment industries and cement/ready-mixed
concrete, the EDB said in releasing the survey.
</P>
<P>
It said that in the electronics industry, business optimism is
mainly led by the computer related industries, particularly the
disk drive sub-segment which anticipates strong demand overseas.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication equipment sub-segment also foresees good
business prospects ahead in the Asia Pacific market. The consumer
electronics, on the other hand, continues to expect a less
favorable business outlook due to sluggish demand, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Survey of Business Expectations of the Manufacturing Sector
for the first quarter of 1997 was conducted by the EDB between
December 1996 and January 1997. Of a total 383 companies surveyed,
94 percent responded.
</P>
<P>
In conducting the survey, companies were asked to indicate
their experience and the expectations of business conditions,
investment and other indicators such as output, employment, orders
and sales, the EDB said.
</P>
<P>
The companies surveyed expect continued growth in export
orders, output and overseas deliveries in the first quarter of
1997, while on investment plans for 1997, a weighted 73 percent of
the manufacturing establishments plan to invest in plants and
machinery, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
