<HEADLINE> U.S. Multinational Pulls out of Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Bechtel International, a U.S.
multinational company has pulled out of an eight-year-old joint
venture pact with the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation,
"The Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said it is still unknown why Bechtel decided to
withdraw from the joint venture, National Engineering and
Technical Company Limited (NETCO), two years before the contract
expires.
</P>
<P>
Bechtel's withdrawal, however, will put at risk no fewer than
15 multi-million-dollar contracts in the hands of NETCO, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
These contracts including engineering services for the
3.8-billion-dollar liquid natural gas project on the Bonny Island
in the Rivers State, NNPC Pipeline Phase three, turn around
maintenance of major Nigerian refineries and others.
</P>
<P>
The Bechtel-NNPC joint venture was launched in 1989 to engage
in engineering services in petroleum and allied industries, with
NNPC holding 60 percent of the shares and Bechtel 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
NNPC officials are now in London to discuss with Bechtel on
the purchase of the latter's equities, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
