<HEADLINE> Kenya Signs U.N. Convention Against Torture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
signed the United Nations Convention Against Torture and is
committed to human rights protection, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
After signing the document, Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo
Musyoka accused international human rights organizations of
judging other countries, yet their operations were "highly
suspect".
</P>
<P>
"Kenya does not practise torture, but you cannot rule out
isolated cases of torture," he said, adding that if cases of
torture are found, the government will take actions against
offenders.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the Convention was a milestone in
Kenya's human rights protection efforts and has signified Kenya
as a responsible U.N. member, he said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the Convention follows earlier appointment of
the Standing Committee on Human Rights by Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi, who accusing Tuesday those criticizing Kenya's human
rights record of using double-standards.
</P>
<P>
"People in Kenya are free and living in peace, while those
countries where people are killing one anothers are said to
respect human rights," said Moi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
