<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea to Exploit Volcano's Geothermal Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Geothermal energy from
beneath dormant volcanos may help to power Eritrea's economic
growth and cut its expensive oil imports, a report reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Baire, a senior official in Eritrea's Ministry of
Mines, Energy and Water Resources, was quoted as saying that
geological survey has shown geothermal potential around volcanic
mount Alid, 80 kilometers south of Red Sea port city Massawa.
</P>
<P>
"As a source of energy, if it becomes viable, there is an
option to produce power in that area... In the long run it could
save costs even though the initial investment is very high," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Baire's ministry has recently received a final report by
Eritrean and American geologists who say there are good prospects
for harnessing geothermal energy from Mount Alid.
</P>
<P>
Mount Alid lies on the geologically active Rift Valley which
arcs from northeast to southern Africa. There geothermal energy
can be harnessed when underground water is boiled by volcanic
heat into steam and then used to generate electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
