<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Strike Palestinian Base Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes launched
this morning an air raid at a base of a radical Palestinian group
near Beirut, but no words on casualties were given by security
sources.
</P>
<P>
The attack came less than 24 hours after a series of
Israeli air strikes at suspected guerrilla targets in the
Syrian-controlled Beqaa Valley in eastern Lebanon, wounding one
Lebanese civilian and three Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that around 10:30 a.m. (8:30 GMT),
Israeli warplanes dived from the clear blue sky and hit the
Naameh hill south of Beirut, where the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command has a camp.
</P>
<P>
The hill was also stricken by Israeli warplanes in Tuesday
afternoon's air raids.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Lebanese government filed a
complaint to a five-nation committee supervising a limited truce
in the border area between Lebanon and Israel, over the Tuesday
successive air raids in eastern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee, comprising representatives
of France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States, was set
up according to a cease-fire understanding reached between Lebanon
and the Jewish state in April, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Radio Lebanon announced this morning that Lebanon
lodged a complaint to the committee's chairman, French diplomat
Jean-Michel Gaussot, over the "wounding of civilians and
destruction of houses."
</P>
<P>
In the complaint, Lebanon accused Israel of violating the
"April understanding," the official radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Brokered by the U.S. and France, the understanding, which put
an end to a 17-day Israeli blitz against Lebanon last April,
barres fighting sides on the last active battlefront of the
Arab-Israeli conflict from targeting civilians.
</P>
<P>
In the first of four sets of air raids in the afternoon, four
Israeli jet fighters pounded a radio station of the Lebanese
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, on the outskirts of the
Shiite Muslim stronghold of Baalbek city 90 kilometers east of
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the Oppressed radio station was badly damaged,
and a 15-year-old shepherd was injured by a number of shrapnels.
</P>
<P>
In another air offensive, two Israeli fighter bombers dropped
two 1,000-kilogram bombs on a base of the PFLP-GC led by Ahamed
Jibril, in the Western Beqaa near the Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
Three Palestinians were wounded in the air raid, the
Damascus-based Palestinian group said.
</P>
<P>
PFLP-GC is among a handful of Palestinian organizations which
are strongly opposed to the peace pursuit led by Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's air raids were the most violent operation Israel
launched in Lebanon since this year.
</P>
<P>
In Israel's "Operation Grapes of Wrath" in south Lebanon
last April, some 200 Lebanese people, mainly civilians, were
killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 People Killed in India's Tripura Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people were killed
and two others injured in violence in West district of Tripura
state in the far east of India today.
</P>
<P>
A group of about 15 ultras armed with sophisticated weapons
opened fired at villagers and burned down their houses, Press
Trust of India (PTI) quoted eyewitnesses as saying.
</P>
<P>
The police have not yet been able to identify the militant
group, but suspected either the All Tripura Tiger Force or the
National Liberation Front of Tripura, as both outfits were active
in the area, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Senior police officials have rushed to the spot. Union Home
Minister Indrajit Gupta visited Tripura state Tuesday to review
the law and order situation there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
