<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Fell Trees Randomly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) has became a major dealer in illegal tree felling in
the world to fund its campaign for a separate Tamil state in Sri
Lanka, according to sources from the north.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that during the period of the LTTE's control
in the Northern Jaffna Peninsula, civilians were prohibited to
cut down trees. But now, they have changed this rule for their own
advantage.
</P>
<P>
After they were driven away from the Jaffna Peninsula and
restricted to the jungles by government troops, the rebels are
felling trees on a mass scale at Batticaloa, Kokavil and Mankulam
jungles in the east of the country, and adding large sums of money
to their coffers to finance their rebel campaign.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE is also involved in drugs, arms and human trafficking
among other unlawful activities, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for a separate Tamil state in the
north and east of the island country since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
