<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes France's Role in Mideast Pease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri said today that his country welcomes the French role in the
Middle East peace process, hoping that this role will be enhanced
after resumption of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the remarks in Paris, France, in an interview
Tuesday with the London-based Al-Hayat daily, the release of which
was available here today.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Arabic daily Al-Hayat today quoted the prime
minister as saying in an interview in Paris that "we welcome the
French role and we are hoping that this role will be strengthened
when the negotiations are resumed."
</P>
<P>
Hariri, currently on a visit to France, had a meeting with
French President Jacques Chirac in Paris Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The coordination between us and Syria, between Lebanon and
France and between France and Syria is big," the Lebanese
premier said.
</P>
<P>
Hariri reiterated his country's refusal of an Israeli
proposal on a conditional withdrawal from Lebanon's land, noting
that "talking about an Israeli withdrawal is a tactical move
rather than a move leading to peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu proposed a unilateral
withdrawal urging the Lebanese government to disarm the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, and intergrates Israel's
proxy militia, the South Lebanon Army, into the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on escalation of tension in south Lebanon,
Hariri said, "I rule out a war (between Israel and its Arab
neighbors) in the region because this is not a realistic thing."
</P>
<P>
"What is necessary is to bring about quickly a start of the
peace negotiations and bring about quickly an Israeli withdrawal
from all the Lebanese and Syrian territories," Hariri pointed
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
