<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concern Expressed over Proposed Electoral System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Trade
Union Congress (MTUC) today said if the proposal to raise
deposits for state and parliamentary election candidates is
implemented, it will result in "politics becoming an elitist
preserve".
</P>
<P>
Expressing deep concern over the proposal, MTUC president
Zainal Rampak said in a statement today that Parliament and state
assemblies would be automatically transformed into an "exclusive
millionaires' clubs" all at the expense of the common people.
</P>
<P>
"Needless to say, such a state of affairs will eventually spell
the end of democracy in our country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement as a powerful reaction to Minister in the
Prime Minister's Department Abang Abu Bakar Mustapha's remarks
Tuesday that the Election Commission would undertake a study on
the possibility of increasing the deposits for state and
parliamentary election candidates.
</P>
<P>
Contestants for state assembly and parliament seats in Malaysia
are presently required to pay a deposit of 3,000 ringgit (about
1,200 U.S. dollars) and 5,000 ringgit (about 2,000 dollars)
respectively. The MTUC leader claimed that arbitrarily increasing
the cost of the electoral process substantially would result in
poor, sincere prospective candidates with good public service
records being disqualified at the starting point itself.
</P>
<P>
The process would "in sum, serve as the fertile breeding ground
for large-scale corruption, money politics vote buying and
political horse- trading", he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to include what he termed
"people-oriented institutions" such as trade unions, societies,
associations and consumer groups in the study group before trying
to effect any significant changes to the electoral system "if at
all there is going to be a study to refine or streamline the
national electoral process".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0139 </DOCNO>
