</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- In 1996, 734,000 babies were born in France, 6,000 more than
in 1995, while 279,000 couples got married, which represents a 10
percent rise over the previous year. This double increase, which
was announced by the official statistics bureau INSEE, backs up a
tendency of population growth which began in 1995 in France.
</P>
<P>
-- While Israeli troops intensified bombing raids on Hezbollah
and Palestinian targets in Lebanon, the Israeli parliament members
are divided over whether to withdraw troops from the self-declared
security zone in southern Lebanon, following the tragic collision of
two military helicopters which killed 73 Israeli soldiers last week.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The ruling majority parties of Rassemblement pour la
Republique and Union pour la Democratic Francaise could face
challenges from the far-right National Front party in 150 to 200
constituencies in the next general elections to be held in 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- The Minister of Agriculture Philippe Vasseur will present a
new agriculture draft law today to the council of ministers. The
text includes an ambitious program which calls for an improvement of
the quality of agricultural products to meet the challenge of
globalization of agricultural trade.
</P>
<P>
-- The Minister of Transport Bernard Pons Tuesday rejected the
demand by striking city bus drivers for early retirement at 55, a
concession made to lorry drivers last November by the government
after they blocked roads across the country for two weeks. 
</P>
