<HEADLINE> Mkapa Casts Graft Net Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
has called upon Tanzanians to join the anti-corruption drive by
exposing corrupt elements in society.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in Biharamulo on Tuesday, the fourth day of
his week-long tour in Kagera region, northwestern Tanzania, Mkapa
said he has given government officials six months to report to
him on the steps taken to curb corruption.
</P>
<P>
The war against corruption at village and ward level is in the
hands of people, he stressed, citing initiatives he had shown
earlier to replace public servants having a tainted record.
</P>
<P>
"I call upon each good citizen who loves his or her country to
report corrupt elements," he appealed.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa asked farmers in the country to elect competent, diligent
and hard-working people as their leaders and encouraged them to
sue leaders guilty of embezzling their funds.
</P>
<P>
He said many cooperative societies in the country are plunged
in serious operational problems, adding that the recent amendment
to the Cooperatives Act of 1981 would give autonomy right to
cooperatives members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
