<HEADLINE> Nominations For Sri Lanka's Local Elections End Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Nominations for Sri Lanka's
local government elections which commenced last Wednesday are due
to end today.
</P>
<P>
Already five registered political parties and 52 independent
groups have submitted nominations. More political parties are
expected to hand in nominations today, according to official
sources here.
</P>
<P>
Elections for 238 local bodies including 11 municipal councils,
31 urban councils and 196 village councils will be held on March
27.
</P>
<P>
The election for the capital city's Colombo Municipal Council
has aroused special interest following the resignation of Mayor K.
Ganeshalingam. The main opposition United National Party (UNP) is
to contest as head of an independent group supported by the ruling
People's Alliance (PA).
</P>
<P>
The UNP's candidate against Ganeshalingam is the party's
chairman Karu Jayasuriya.
</P>
<P>
Following the outbreak of violence at some nomination centers
Tuesday, all public processions have been banned.
</P>
<P>
Police this morning announced tighter security in and around
all district secretariats to prevent further pre-election violence
after the incident at Kuruwita town Tuesday evening where
Ratnapura District member of parliament Nalanda Ellawala was shot
dead and five others were injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Household Tend to Buy More Securities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey has shown that
Beijing residents are holding more securities as monetary assets,
though many still keep their money safely deposited in banks, the
Guangming Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by the Beijing Statistics Bureau among 1,550
households, the survey indicates that every household has an
average of 39,873 yuan, 79.4 percent of which is in bank deposits,
12.1 percent is in securities and 3.4 percent is cash.
</P>
<P>
The surveyors found a rising demand among residents for buying
state treasury bonds, with about 74.4 percent of securities in the
form of treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1996, household monetary assets rose 7.2 times on
the whole, while securities and banking deposits increased 8.8
times and 7.3 times respectively, but cash in hand rose only 1.3
times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
