<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, NDF Rebels to Step Up Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos was informed here today that the peace panels of the
government and the rebelling National Democratic Front (NDF) have
agreed to step up their peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Howard Dee, chairman of the government panel, told the
president that the two sides have agreed to accelerate
negotiations in the next four months in order to reach a final
peace settlement by June this year.
</P>
<P>
Dee said that both panels will discuss the human rights
agreement in March, economic and social reforms and perhaps,
political and electoral reforms in April, and the "end of
hostilities and disposition of forces" in June.
</P>
<P>
He said the two panels, which held an eight-day meeting in
Utrecht, the Netherlands, earlier this month, have agreed on the
mode of release for NDF consultant Danilo Borjal on or before
February 18.
</P>
<P>
The meeting began and proceeded as an informal meeting for
several days and became formal after the two panels successfully
hammered out a number of important agreements, which will be
subjected for approval by their respective principals, Dee said.
</P>
<P>
The government signed a peace agreement with the mainstream
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) last year, ending a
24-year-old war in the southern Philippines. It is now pursuing
peace talks with the NDF and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, a
splinter group of the MNLF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
