<HEADLINE> Moi Condemns Use of Children in Zaire's Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has condemned the conscription of primary school students
into Zaire's rebel army, terming it as an abuse of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Keiyo District of Rift Valley province on Tuesday,
the president said the rebel leader, Laurent Kabila, is using
children as pawns in pursuit of egocentric goals in the name of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
Children must always be given a chance to develop in a
peaceful environment so that they can realize their full
potential, the Kenyan leader added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that human life is abused daily in many parts
of Africa as unsuitable democracy was introduced into the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader had reportedly been walking into classrooms
to conscript students into his army in the last few days in the
face of a counter-offensive by Zairean government troops.
</P>
<P>
Kabila presided over a parade of more than 1,000 new rebel
recruits on Monday at the Roman Catholic secondary school in
Bukavu, appealing to parents in eastern Zaire to encourage their
sons to join his rebel army.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that he commands an army of up tou 15,000
rebels, most of whom are children of around the age of 15 years.
</P>
