<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has become
the most murderous country in the world under the governance of
the African National Congress (ANC), National Party (NP) leader
F. W. De Klerk said.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk made the remarks for the first time on Tuesday under
his new title of Leader of the official opposition since NP's
withdrawal from the ANC-led Government of National Unity in May
last year, a local daily "The Citizen" today reported.
</P>
<P>
During the debate on President Nelson Mandela's speech opening
Parliament in Cape Town, De Klerk said the promises and threats
regarding rampant crime made by Mandela needed to be translated
into assertive action and deeds.
</P>
<P>
During the period Mandela delivered his speech to the new
session of parliament last Friday, said De Klerk, six women had
been raped in South Africa, 40 people assaulted, nine motor
vehicles hijacked and three murders committed.
</P>
<P>
While referring to the reconciliation, the opposition leader
also accused the ANC of plunging the country into a form of new
apartheid by fomenting color prejudices, citing the policy of the
affirmative action, which the blacks were reportedly favored than
the whites in the public services and parastatals.
</P>
<P>
"This is a dead-end street which could only end in crisis and
misery," De Klerk claimed. 
</P>
