<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases 30 Palestinian Women Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel released overnight
30 Palestinian women prisoners in a positive gesture that will
help push forward to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Thirty of the 31 prisoners slated for release left prisons by
11:30 (21:30 GMT) Tuesday night. Only Zinav Sido, convicted of
selling drugs in 1994, remained at Neveh Tirza Prison.
</P>
<P>
The release was agreed upon at a meeting between Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The release was held up for almost a day as Israel's High Court
of Justice rejected a last-minute petition against the
government's decision to pardon the prisoners, which was filed by
the rightist Association of Terror Victims (ATV). A day earlier,
the court rejected a similar petition by the ATV.
</P>
<P>
All the women were reportedly freed on condition that they
signed a statement pledging not to return to violent attacks
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Lamya Maarouf, a 32-year-old Brazilian citizen, was the first
to be released Tuesday afternoon. She was sentenced to 25 years
in jail in 1986 after being convicted of kidnaping and killing
an Israeli soldier. Palestinian officials said she would be
deported after the release.
</P>
<P>
Most of the released women were taken to the Palestinian city
of Ramallah, where several hundreds of people, mostly the
relatives of the prisoners, gathered before the police
headquarters to welcome them home.
</P>
<P>
Despite of presence of Arafat in the welcoming ceremony, the
celebration was very low-key in order to avoid provoking the
extremist Jews.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Israeli police detained two rightist
Jews who tried to block the buses transporting the Palestinian
detainees from leaving a prison.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Arafat praised the release of
Palestinian women prisoners as a good sign for peace with
Israel. "No doubt this will help the relationship between the two
peoples," he said.
</P>
<P>
All the women prisoners were to have been released immediately
after the signing of the Oslo II accords in September 1995, but
Israeli President Ezer Weizman refused to pardon two of them, who
were convicted of killing Jews.
</P>
<P>
In a goodwill gesture after his meeting with Arafat in the wake
of the September bloodshed, due to Israel's opening of a tunnel
near the holy site Al Aqsa Mosque in Jerusalem, Weizman changed
his mind by agreeing to pardon also the two murderers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu demanded
Tuesday the PNA to fulfill its own obligations to the peace
accords after Israel's release of the women prisoners.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a tactic, we are serious about fulfilling
commitments, but we intend fully to see that there is an equal
reciprocity on the other sides," he said during a tour to the
northern border.
</P>
<P>
He specifically urged the PNA to stop all political activities
in eastern Jerusalem according to the Oslo accords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0155 </DOCNO>
