<HEADLINE> China in Urgent Need of Qualified Public Accountants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has become the tenth province to unite its two
associations of auditors and accountants -- a move regarded as a
milestone in the nationwide reform of the accounting workforce.
</P>
<P>
China started to bring together its organizations for auditors
and accountants in 1995, in a move to better discipline the
accounting field and sever the ties the accounting agencies once
had with the government.
</P>
<P>
"This process will sharpen the competitive edge of Chinese
accountants, helping them edge into the international accounting
market and comply with international accounting norms," observed
Ding Pingzhun, Secretary General of the China Association of
Certified Public Accountants.
</P>
<P>
Ten provinces and autonomous regions have so far completed the
work, bringing the number of members of the Association of
Certified Public Accountants to well over 70,000.
</P>
<P>
That figure will exceed 110,000 when the reform is completed.
</P>
<P>
But China needs even more accountants than that: a team of
300,000 certified public accountants is predicted to be a
necessity by the end of this century, with the rapidly increasing
number of overseas-funded ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
China has also vowed to adopt a unified code to audit the
accounting sheets of large- and medium-sized state firms before
the end of 1997. The code will apply to all Chinese enterprises by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"This also poses an urgent need to train more certified public
accountants," Ding stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
