<HEADLINE> Thai Minister Urges Dealers to Deliver Cars on Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai Commerce Minister
Narongchai Akrasanee has warned that car makers and dealers must
deliver ordered vehicles to customers on time or face penalties.
</P>
<P>
Narongchai reminded car makers and dealers that under existing
regulations vehicles must be supplied within three months of
booking and that they must pay interest to customers who had made
down payments, or refund the deposit.
</P>
<P>
His warning Tuesday followed heavy bookings for Toyota's new
Soluna, a budget-priced sedan.
</P>
<P>
Customers are worried that the existing assembly capacity of
Toyota Motor (Thailand) Co. might not be able to deliver the
ordered cars on time.
</P>
<P>
The company has collected booking fees totaling 145 million
baht (5.8 million U.S. dollars) based on 29,000 orders for the
Soluna, with each customer paying a deposit of 5,000 baht (200
dollars).
</P>
<P>
It is worried that based on the company's existing production
capacity, customers may have to wait six months for their ordered
cars.
</P>
<P>
The company said it would boost assembly capacity next month in
Thailand from 3,000 to 5,000 per month to ensure punctual
deliveries.
</P>
<P>
An Internal Trade Department source said Toyota aimed to sell
40,000 Solunas this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
