<HEADLINE> Colombia's Civil Servants Strike for Higher Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 600,000
government employees in Colombia went on an indefinite nationwide
strike today in support of their demands for higher pay.
</P>
<P>
The strike, called by the National Federation of State Workers,
the Unitary Workers' Union, the Colombian Workers' Union and the
General Confederation of Democratic Workers, began at midnight
local time.
</P>
<P>
About 600,000 to 650,000 people, nearly 70 percent of the
country's public servants, took part in the strike, union
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Union leaders argued that the 13.5 percent salary hike decreed
earlier by the government was an insult to public servants since
last year's inflation was 21.65 percent. They asked for new
negotiations with the government to further increase their wages.
</P>
<P>
They also opposed the privatization of state-owned companies
and violence against union movements.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, international airlines including American Airlines
and Continental Airlines suspended operations in Colombia, fearing
the strike could spread to other sectors including communications.
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Samper Pizano said Monday evening on the
national radio network that "murky interests" were behind the
strike to "sow the seeds of chaos and violence".
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Horacio Serpa asked the strikers to behave
with prudence and good judgment to avoid being taken advantage of
by drug traffickers and guerillas.
</P>
<P>
Government authorities said security forces are on alert
throughout the country to prevent any possible disturbances.
</P>
</TEXT>
