<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Gears to Single Market, Customs Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) is set for a single market and a
customs union by the end of the century, according to the local
press today.
</P>
<P>
The report by quoting COMESA Director of Trade and Customs
Vewde Demissie as saying that the commitment followed recent
recommendations by the COMESA Trade and Customs Committee to the
Council of Ministers which pledged a schedule of Common External
Tariffs (CET).
</P>
<P>
This agreement was arrived at after extensive discussions of
various studies regarding the establishment of CET, the global
liberalization after the Uruguay round agreement and the
liberalization trends within COMESA.
</P>
<P>
the agreement on a schedule of CET for COMESA facilitates the
establishment of a single market with a population of 320
million, Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of 80 billion U.S. Dollars,
and import bill of 19 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
It provides vast opportunities of national, cross-border and
direct foreign investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The decision to establish CET also took into account the
economic competitiveness of member countries, impact of a common
external tariff on government revenue, protection of domestic
industries, intra-COMESA trade, COMESA trade with third countries
and on consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA Council of Ministers is expected to discuss CET
recommendations in Lusaka on April 7-8 to prepare the agenda for
the COMESA Heads of State and Government meeting on April 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
