<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Signs 1997 National Budget Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos signed here today into law the 1997 national budget totaling
493.1 billion pesos (18.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was approved after two months' hot debate
between the two chambers of Congress, is 16.5 billion pesos (630
million U.S. dollars) higher than the amount originally proposed
by the president.
</P>
<P>
"The passage of the budget law ensures the continuity of the
strong fiscal foundation we have carefully laid out since I took
office in 1992," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos commended Congress for reflecting in the budget his
proposal that the largest chunk of the budget should continue to
go to social services.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the increase in capital outlays in the budget,
saying it will enable the government to improve its capital stock
and other more-enduring investments that will build up the
country's capability for self-sustaining development.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos vetoed nine items in the budget, which include
the provision banning the Commission on Elections to appropriate
funds for any elections or plebiscites for the purpose of amending
the Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
