<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Aims Record Export of Electronics and Machinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of
China (EximBank) will increase loans to the country's exporters of
electronics and other capital goods to push the export volume well
over 80 billion US dollars during the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
EximBank's credit for exports this year is planned at 19.7
billion yuan and 101 million US dollars, as against the actual
amount of 14 billion yuan last year and two billion yuan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Its export seller's credits, valued at 22.4 billion yuan and 54
million US dollars, have financed 7.26 billion US dollars worth of
electronics and machinery exports so far.
</P>
<P>
This included 170 vessels, 34 aircraft, and launching services
for six satellites.
</P>
<P>
The bank also made marked progress in tapping the export credit
insurance and guarantee fields, with the business volumes standing
at 770 million and 530 million US dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
EximBank was set up in April of 1994 to provide policy-oriented
funding for the export of electronics and machinery products. It
already has agent bank relations with 113 banks in 83 countries
and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
