<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, U.S. to Launch New Anti-missile Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the United
States plan to launch a new anti-missile program this summer
that aims to destroy enemy ballistic missiles in early stage,
a report said today.
</P>
<P>
The program, called Boost-Phased Intercept (BPI), would begin
with a risk-reduction phase that will ensure a consequently
smoother research and development program, Israeli officials were
quoted by today's The Jerusalem Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the phase would cost 34 million
U.S. dollars which were to be shared by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the U.S. Congress provided 15 million dollars
for a multi-year feasibility study of BPI. At present, senior
defense officials are quietly making the rounds in Congress to
ensure that the funding will be available for the next
phase, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Boost-Phased-Intercept, a concept that remains unproven, calls
for the destruction of enemy missiles in their early stage of
launch when the projectiles are still low in the sky and moving
slowly. One approach is to use an early-warning airborne radar
system to detect the launches and direct another plane to fire a
laser beam that would destroy the enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
"We are coming up with all sorts of projects on how to
deal with Scud-type missiles," a senior Israeli defense official
said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of BPI was discussed last month during the
visit to Israel of the new head of the U.S. Ballistic
Missile Defense Organization, U.S. Air Force Lt.- Gen. Lester
Lyles.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials confirmed that Lyles returned from Israel on
January 29 with a draft agreement to build a prototype of
unmanned aerial vehicles designed to intercept enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
Israeli defense sources maintain that the U.S. government is
showing growing interest in BPI. They also said the main
contractor for the BPI program would be Israel Aircraft
Industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Adopts Regulation to Control Drug-Making Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
Province, which yearly confiscates large amounts of chemicals that
can be used to make drugs, has enacted a local law to crack down
on the use of special chemicals or pharmaceuticals needed to
produce illegal substances.
</P>
<P>
Adopted recently by the provincial people's congress, the
regulation lists 28 chemical products that can be easily turned
into drugs. They include ephedrine for making the drug "ice," and
acetic anhydride, ether and chloroform for making heroin.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulated that ventures or companies that make, sell,
transport and use the listed chemicals must receive special
licensing. Those units are prohibited from providing any of the
listed chemicals overseas.
</P>
<P>
The regulation added that businesses or individuals that
illegally make, sell or transport the listed chemicals will be
fined between 5,000 to 10,000 yuan (600 to 1,200 U.S. dollars) and
their products and vehicles used to transport the drugs will be
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Those who smuggle the listed chemicals abroad will be punished
as drug runners in accordance with the state law.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is famous for its rubber trees, and the chemical agents
such as acetic anhydride, ether and chloroform are usually used as
a coagulating agent in the processing of rubber latex.
</P>
<P>
Ephedrine can be used to treat asthma and rhinitis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: ASEAN, EU to Seek Common Ground  Despite Differences by Liu Huorong, Zeng Hu (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- As their foreign ministers
are arriving in the Lion City for a two-day meeting today, the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the European
Union (EU) seem set to give another push to their 20-year-old
relationship of dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At their two-day meeting beginning Thursday, foreign ministers
from the seven ASEAN and 15 EU countries will "review the ASEAN-EU
dialogue relationship and set future directions for the ASEAN-EU
dialogue," the Foreign Ministry of Singapore, the host, said in a
press statement issued on the eve of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN-EU dialogue is important for both strategic and
economic reasons," Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar said in
a recent interview with the press. "We are working hard to ensure
that the 12th ASEAN-EU Ministerial Meeting (AEMM) in Singapore
will give an added impetus to the relationship."
</P>
<P>
The two regional groupings have built up an extensive network
of commercial, economic and political relations since 1977 when
their ties were formalized as the EC became an ASEAN dialogue
partner and was invited to attend the First ASEAN Post-Ministerial
Conference.
</P>
<P>
In the following year, the two organizations decided to open
negotiations for a cooperation agreement, which was signed in 1980
and is still in force today, having been amended to include Brunei
Darussalam in 1985. And according to the program of the coming
12th ASEAN-EU Ministerial Meeting, the accord will be further
amended to include Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Analysis: ASEAN, EU to Seek Common Ground  Despite Differences (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
And over the years, the two sides have become each other's
major trading partners. Official figures show that in 1995, EU
exports to the ASEAN reached 52.88 billion U.S. dollars, out of a
total of 1.911 trillion dollars, while exports from the ASEAN to
the EU amounted to 46.63 billion dollars, out of a total of 249.48
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam while the EU has as
its members Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany,
Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal,
Spain, Sweden and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a review of the ties between the two organizations,
the 12th ASEAN-EU Ministerial Meeting (AEMM) is also expected to
discuss issues such as economic relations, political issues,
development cooperation and other people-to-people activities
before adopting a joint declaration, which a Singapore Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman said "can be expected to put in place a
framework that will guide relations into the next century."
</P>
<P>
But despite the two sides' determination to focus on common
ground during the meeting, difference may erupt, particularly over
issues such as East Timor and Myanmar, which were raised at AEMM
meetings in the past.
</P>
<P>
At the Senior Officials Meeting here which started Tuesday to
prepare for the Ministerial Meeting, EU officials have indicated
that they are going to raise the two issues and want to include
them in the joint declaration to be issued at the end of the
meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: ASEAN, EU to Seek Common Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ASEAN however has made it clear that these two questions
should be excluded.
</P>
<P>
"A fundamental principle of ASEAN member states is that we do
not comment on the internal situation, nor interfere in, the
domestic politics of other countries," Singapore Foreign Minister
Jayakumar said. "With regard to Myanmar, the ASEAN approach of
constructive engagement remains the most useful."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, at its informal summit in Indonesia last year,
agreed to admit Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos simultaneously,
hopefully before the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
In regard to the issue of East Timor, which the EU may raise at
the meeting as it did in the past, Jayakumar believed that the
ASEAN-EU Ministerial Meeting is not an appropriate forum.
</P>
<P>
"It is an issue which is between Indonesia and Portugal and
should not be introduced into the ASEAN-EU level relationship," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has already threatened to walk out of the meeting
should the EU or Portugal raise the question, a Singapore Foreign
Ministry official said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The country claims East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, as
part of its territory while Portugal insists that the people there
should be given the right to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
"The Association of Southeast Asian Nations and the European
Union are at a critical point in their relationship," an ASEAN-EU
ad hoc Eminent Persons Group pointed out in a report, which spells
out the strategies for a new partnership between the two groupings
and which will be discussed by the foreign ministers at their
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Over a wide range of issues, the leaders of the two groupings
have now to choose the route which they wish to follow into the
next century. In particular, they have the opportunity to decide
whether to pursue their way together and, if so, how.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
