<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8,123 College Students Donate Blood in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 8,123 college
students in the Chinese capital voluntarily donated blood in 1996,
representing nearly one third of the city's final tally of donors
for the year.
</P>
<P>
According to the blood donation target set for Beijing-based
colleges and universities, including the well-known Qinghua
University and Beijing University, 25,458 people were needed to
give blood in 1996, a rise of 20 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Evening News reported that 25,798 people, including the
college students, gave blood in 1996. Among the donors were
post-graduates studying for their masters or doctoral degree,
college professors and staff.
</P>
<P>
A local regulation on blood donation stipulates that all
undergraduates, mainly those in their third academic year, are to
give blood once during their college career.
</P>
<P>
The practice of student blood donations has been successful in
colleges and universities throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, recently
issued a regulation asking each of its healthy residents to donate
blood once every five years.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 11 provincial and city legislative bodies or
governments in China set official guidelines for blood donation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
