<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 128 Zimbabweans This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaria killed 128 Zimbabweans
countrywide in the first five weeks of this year, while another
66,556 cases were reported during the same period, a health
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Health and Child Welfare Ministry Paulinus
Sikosana said here on Tuesday that as a result, the government is
moving swiftly and has released two million U.S. Dollars to fight
the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
At least 1.3 million U.S. Dollars have been used to buy
insecticides to spray water ponds, houses, huts and other places
favored by mosquitoes, and another 700,000 Dollars were used to
buy anti-malaria drugs, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sikosana said his ministry anticipated the malaria problem to
be bigger this year than last year because of the incessant and
widespread rains, a situation which created a conducive
environment for mosquito breeding.
</P>
<P>
Last year, malaria killed more than 2,000 Zimbabwean people.
</P>
</TEXT>
