<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Selects 7 Hydro Projects for Feasibility Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
selected seven medium-size hydropower projects throughout the
country for feasibility study under a loan assistance program,
electricity planning officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The seven projects, with a total generating capacity of nearly
600 megawatt, are mostly located in hilly areas of western and
eastern Nepal, officials of the Medium Hydropower Study Project
(MHSP) were quoted by local newspapers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of these proposed projects have been chosen for
feasibility study after one year of preliminary study under the
MHSP, which is financed by a five million US dollar loan from the
International Development Agency, they said.
</P>
<P>
The MHSP project, implemented by the Nepal Electricity
Authority (NEA), the governing body of the country's power sector,
is part of the government's electricity planning process which
involves completion of technical and environmental studies to
start the project financing.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government earlier has adopted a policy to encourage
private investors to develop hydropower projects, especially small
and medium-size ones, in the country which has an estimated
hydroelectric potential of some 83,000 megawatt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
