<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force Resumes Coastal Training Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force resumed
training flights along parts of the country's coastlines today
after a four-day suspension following accidents involving military
planes and commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the Air Force is
redesigning its training to take into account the sensitivity of
collision avoidance systems on civilian planes.
</P>
<P>
He said one of the things investigators discovered was that
many commercial planes' alerts can be triggered off by fighter
jets at distances the military pilots may not be counting on.
</P>
<P>
Two incidents occurred last Wednesday off the East Coast of
Maryland and New Jersey involving commercial aircraft and F-16 Air
National Guard jets that prompted a suspension of training
missions along the coast.
</P>
<P>
In one of the cases, collision alarms sounded in an airliner
when F-16 fighters came too close, causing one airline pilot to
maneuver so sharply that three people were thrown to the floor. In
the other case, the pilot went into a descent to avoid the
military planes.
</P>
<P>
Two more incidents were reported on Friday. One took place when
two F-16s and an American Airlines MD-80 passenger jet came too
close near Clovis, New Mexico. The second incident was between one
F-16 and a Northwest Airlines Airbus about 117 kilometers
southwest of Palacios, Texas.
</P>
<P>
In the New Mexico incident, a collision warning was triggered
aboard an American Airlines MD-80 jetliner and the pilot climbed
to avoid coming close to the military planes.
</P>
<P>
The F-16s were about 5.6 kilometers from the airliner and
flying within 90 meters of the airliner's altitude at the time,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
In the Texas incident, an F-16 came within 7.7 kilometers
horizontally and 90 meters vertically of a Northwest Airbus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration on Friday ordered
controllers at its Jacksonville, Florida, Washington and New York
air traffic control centers and military controllers at the
Virginia Capes station to review procedures for handling traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
