<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parties Agree To Support Caretaker Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The five main parties in the
Bulgarian parliament agreed on Tuesday to support a caretaker
cabinet until elections are held in April, the Bulgarian Telegraph
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a meeting called by President
Petar Stoanov Tuesday afternoon, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the five parties in parliament agreed to give full
powers to the caretaker government which will be appointed by
Stoanov to deal temporarily with the country's economic crisis,
including signing loan and assistance contracts with international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time this month Bulgaria's politicians have
reached agreement, propelled by escalating protests and the
economic disaster which has engulfed the country.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria plunged into a political crisis after the previous
Socialist prime minister resigned in December over his handling of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Although the Socialist government was only half-way through its
four-year mandate, the opposition and outgoing president protested
against the Socialists forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
Pressure mounted on the Socialists as people took to the
streets in massive daily protests calling for early elections.
</P>
<P>
The parties finally signed an agreement on February 4 on
holding a general election on April 19 this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the parliamentary group led by the ruling
Socialists gave up its chance to form a government.
</P>
<P>
The caretaker government is expected to function for about
three months, the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency said, adding that
Sofia city mayor Stefan Sofianski was likely to be appointed prime
minister of the caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
Sofianski himself did not confirm or rule out the
possibility. But he told reporters Tuesday that the caretaker
government would make all-out efforts to negotiate with the
International Monetary Fund for loans and assistance.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's economy has almost collapsed over the last year as
prices skyrocketed and living standards fell dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The political crisis added fuel to the fire; the currency, the
lev, has fallen five-fold to about 2,500 to the U.S. dollar since
January 1.
</P>
<P>
Monthly inflation was put at 50 percent in January alone and
average monthly wages have plummeted in value to less than 10
dollars compared to 70 dollars a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
