<HEADLINE> India Relaxes Coal Exploration Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
decided to allow private participation including foreign
companies, in the exploration and mining of coal, a government
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet decision made on Tuesday will be applicable only
after the government changes the coal/mines (nationalization) act
1957, through an amendment approved by parliament as the act
prohibits the entry of private companies in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The government will also have to amend the mines and minerals
(regulation and development) act 1957 in order to permit private
companies to undertake exploration work.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies would be allowed into the sector only through
joint ventures with the Indian companies subject to the approval
from the foreign investment promotion board (FIPB).
</P>
<P>
The extent of equity participation of the foreign companies
would depend on the FIPB formula fixed by the government from time
to time, the same source said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government currently allows 50 percent foreign
equity in exploration and mining and 74 percent in mining
services.
</P>
<P>
The entry of private sector was necessary to bring in advanced
technology, the official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
