<HEADLINE> Russia Warns of Retaliation Against NATO's Expansion Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia would have to take
retaliatory measures if NATO insisted on its plans for eastward
expansion, Secretary of the Russian Security Council Ivan Rybkin
said today.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Danish Defense Minister Hans
Haekkenup, Rybkin stressed that NATO's expansion would result in
great changes in the political situation within Russia and
seriously threaten the country's democratic reform process.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly expressed its strong opposition against
NATO's expansion plans since the 16-member alliance officially
announced the plan in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin reiterated that NATO's plan had not been anticipated by
Russian leaders, who believed the alliance would disintegrate
after the Warsaw Pact bloc was disbanded in the wake of the
collapse of the Soviet Union in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Warsaw Pact bloc was NATO's arch rival in the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin indicated that cooperation between Russia and NATO was
possible if the latter agreed to sign an independent agreement
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
He added that Europe's security should be guaranteed by the
joint efforts of all countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Rybkin's remark coincided with a current tour by NATO Secretary
General Javier Solana of the four former Soviet republics of
Moldova, Georgia, Armenia and Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Another report from the Interfax news agency quoted Dmitry
Ryurikov, Russian President Boris Yeltsin's top foreign policy
adviser, as saying that Solana's tour was aimed at showing NATO's
tough line on the expansion issue.
</P>
<P>
Ryurikov said Solana's tour was also a signal to the four
nations that NATO's door was open to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
