<HEADLINE> Albania's Ruling Democrats to Discuss Solutions to Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister
Alexander Meksi said today that his administration was trying to
restore peace through dialogue in the southern port of Vlore,
where three people died in rioting this week.
</P>
<P>
Meksi said the government has decided to postpone the
declaration of a state of emergency in the city following clashes
between the police and protesters who lost their life savings in a
string of collapsed pyramid investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
Widespread rioting swept Albania last month after pyramid
schemes offering quick returns started to go bust. The schemes had
attracted money from virtually every family in the country of 3.4
million people over the past six years. Citizens in Vlore suffered
the biggest losses.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has blamed the government for the failure of the
investment schemes and demanded the resignation of the government.
</P>
<P>
President Sali Berisha convened an emergency meeting of the
parliamentary group of the ruling Democratic Party on
Monday. Members of the group debated the situation in Vlore and
the whole country and measures to control the situation. 
</P>
