<HEADLINE> Thailand Plans Tax Refund to Help Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) will complete guidelines for tax refund for foreign
tourists in the first half of this year to boost Thailand as a
shopping center in the Southeast Asian region, according to local
press today.
</P>
<P>
In principle, the planned tax refund system drafted by the TAT
will specify a minimum spending limit over which tourists can
claim a tax refund at the airport before leaving Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is hoped to be a big attraction to lure foreign
tourists to spend more money on shopping, similar to systems
operating in Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The 7 percent value-added tax refund program for foreign
tourists is to be launched this year in preparation for the
revisit Thailand year in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The TAT hopes it will be a strong selling point for the
country, beyond the well-known traditional Thai culture and
natural locations.
</P>
<P>
Pannara Choochan, deputy governor for marketing at the TAT, was
quoted as saying that the aim of becoming a shopping center will
be achieved in stages, so problems regarding tax refunds, quality
control of products, experience of traders, as well as duty free
shops for tourists can be addressed in stages.
</P>
<P>
The year 1998, he said, will be best opportunity to turn
Thailand into a shopping center. Thailand in that year will host
the Asian Games which will generate many activities throughout the
year. It is expected more tourists will visit Thailand in 1998 --
about one percent increase from an estimated 7.5 million this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
