<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Budget Cuts to Reduce Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic growth
rate for this year is expected to fall to 6.8 percent from an
earlier forecast of 7.1 percent, as a result of massive budget
cuts proposed by the government.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on Tuesday, the cabinet decided to cut 99 billion
baht (3.96 billion US dollars) from the fiscal 1997 budget
standing at 984 billion baht (39.36 billion dollars), to ease the
country's current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
Specific projects to be cut are yet to be decided. But those
deemed to be unproductive, non-urgent or having a high import
content are likely to be axed.
</P>
<P>
Of the proposed cuts, the government spending will be reduced
by 59 billion baht (2.36 billion dollars), while state enterprises
will face a reduction of at least 40 billion baht (1.6 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The pruning is aimed at lowering the current account deficit,
which reached 8.3 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) last
year.
</P>
<P>
If the planned cuts are implemented, the country's current
account deficit for 1997 would drop to 7.4 percent of GDP, from
8.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's fiscal year 1997 ends on September 30 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
