<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Congress Names New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's Congress today
selected its leader Fabian Alarcon as the country's interim
president, hours after Acting President Rosalia Arteaga's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
Alarcon, now 50, got the job by winning a majority of
congressional votes. He will act as an interim president to govern
the country until 1998, when he is supposed to call new elections.
</P>
<P>
The selection of an interim president was in line with an
earlier deal between Acting President Arteaga and Congress amid a
political turmoil in this small Andean nation.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the two sides agreed that Vice President Arteaga
would act as president until legislators name an interim president
to replace ousted President Abdala Bucaram.
</P>
<P>
Arteaga refused to give up her post as caretaker president on
Monday, insisting that Congress would have to amend the country's
constitution before it could elect an interim president.
</P>
<P>
But she changed her mind later and declared she would return to
her vice presidency held in the Bucaram administration.
</P>
<P>
In a letter announcing her resignation, Arteaga proposed a
national referendum to decide what role Congress should play when
the presidency becomes vacant and whether she should retain the
post of vice president.
</P>
<P>
On a previous occasion, Alarcon was sworn in as interim
president by legislators last week immediately after they voted to
oust Bucaram on the grounds of "mental incapacity."
</P>
<P>
But as an elected president, Bucaram refused to step down. And
Arteaga claimed that under the country's constitution, she should
assume the presidency when the post becomes vacant.
</P>
<P>
It was through the military's mediation that the vice president
and Congress worked out an agreement that resulted in Arteaga's
taking of the presidential office for two days.
</P>
<P>
Bucaram, who left here today on a chartered plane for Panama,
said he was still the president. "I never resigned and will never
resigned," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called Congress' action to oust him a dangerous
precedent. "Now Congress can meet and overthrow a president in 10
minutes," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
