<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Opposes Canada's Whaling Permit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
responded today to Canada's "unacceptable" decision to authorize
whaling by brushing aside Canadian request for trade in seals.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's unilateral decision to authorize whaling outside of
the IWC (International Whaling Commission) is unacceptable,"
Clinton said in a letter to Congress. "Canada's conduct
jeopardizes the international effort that has allowed whale stocks
to begin to recover from the devastating effects of historic
whaling."
</P>
<P>
Washington's reaction was to Canadian government's alleged
decision last year to issue whaling licenses to native hunters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government said that the move undermined the
conservation program of the IWC aimed at protecting the endangered
bowhead. Canada is not a member of the IWC.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he had instructed the U.S. Commerce Department to
suspend consideration of any Canadian requests for waivers to the
existing moratorium on the import of seals and seal products into
the United States.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the U.S. State Department to oppose Canadian
efforts to address takings of marine mammals within the newly
formed Arctic Council.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president said he felt these measures were more
appropriate than imposing an import ban on Canadian fish
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
