<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Prepares Concept Paper on Sub-regional Grouping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
preparing a concept paper on sub-regional cooperation among
Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Bhutan, spelling out the framework
and objectives of the proposed idea, according to the Foreign
Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
The paper will be placed at a specially convened meeting of
foreign secretaries of the four countries, which is likely to take
place in Kathmandu sometime in March for launching the idea on
more concrete terms, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries' meeting is likely to be followed by a
meeting of the foreign ministers of the concerned four countries.
</P>
<P>
The idea of sub-regional cooperation was first floated by
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad at the SAARC foreign
ministers conference held in New Delhi in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC)
also includes Pakistan, Sri Lanka and the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
The concept paper proposed by Dhaka will aim at identifying the
areas of cooperation between the four neighboring countries. The
paper will also try to explore the possibilities of undertaking
some steps under a common platform to address some identical
problems confronting the four countries.
</P>
<P>
The issues may include the problems of illegal trafficking of
women and children, cross-border trade and smuggling. Some common
concerns like environmental degradation will also be addressed.
</P>
<P>
Although harnessing of water resources is seen as a crucial
area, this may take a back seat at the formative stage of the
sub-regional concept, the sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
