<HEADLINE> Mostar Still Tense After Monday's Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia's divided city of
Mostar remained tense today following Monday's clash between the
Muslims and Croats, in which five people were killed and 46
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Alije Izetbegovic, Chairman of the three-man Presidency of
Bosnia and leader of the Bosnian Muslims, and Kresimir Zubak, a
Croat member of the presidency, urged people in Mostar not to take
any action which could escalate the violence in the city.
</P>
<P>
A night-time curfew was declared in Mostar after Monday's
trouble when Bosnian Croats opened fire on Muslim pilgrims trying
to visit a cemetery in Croat-controlled west Mostar. Two people
were killed and 22 were injured.
</P>
<P>
In revenge, the Muslims attacked Croat vehicles passing
Muslim-controlled east Mostar, leaving two Croats dead, 24 wounded
and 20 vehicles damaged.
</P>
<P>
Croats then evicted some 26 Muslim families out of west Mostar.
</P>
<P>
The multi-national stabilization force Sfor arrived at the
demarcation line to separate the two sides and patrol the streets
in a bid to prevent the conflict from worsening.
</P>
<P>
Both the Muslims and Croats blamed each other for starting the
conflict. Representatives of the international community in Bosnia
are investigating the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
