<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Enters 1997 With Big Increase in Capital Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Peru entered 1997 with a
seven-fold increase in foreign investment in the first five weeks
of the year compared with that of last month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 1.14 billion U.S. dollars new capital inflow, registered as
of February 5, topped the 62.6 billion dollars total that the
country had already received at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The National Committee on Foreign Technology and Investment
said the communications sector claimed a lion's share of the
influx, or nearly a third of the increase in the five-week period.
</P>
<P>
Energy, mining and manufacturing sectors trailed with 18
percent, 16 percent and 15 percent of the new gains respectively.
</P>
<P>
Among the biggest investors in this South American country are
Spain, the United States and the Great Britain, which represented
72.3 percent of the total investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
