<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks to Boost Science Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The National Research Council
(NRC) of Thailand Tuesday launched an ambitious five-year master
plan which emphasized the urgent need to build a national
"knowledge bank" in science and technology to increase Thailand's
competitiveness in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which will run from this year to 2001, is seen as an
attempt to revamp the country's research policy.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time we have drafted a systematic research
policy and plan to tackle the country's fundamental problems of
poverty, look at the need to increase people' quality of life, and
our future industrial competitiveness," Suwit Wiboonset, secretary
general of the NRC was quoted by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The NRC was optimistic that the new master plan will lead the
country to sustainable development as it was developed to solve
the country's fundamental problems as well as to prepare Thailand
for new international relationships in the 21th century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
