<HEADLINE> Human Rights Irrelevant in Asia-EU Talks: Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Human rights and East Timor
issues shall not be raised when foreign ministers of Southeast
Asian and European Union (EU) hold their meeting in Singapore this
week, an Indonesian parliamentary leader said.
</P>
<P>
"The issues are not relevant," Chairperson of the House
Commission 1 dealing with international affairs Aisjah Aminy said
here last night.
</P>
<P>
"Concern on human rights is a must, but it should be in an
appropriate forum," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian-EU cooperation must be improved to be a win-win
cooperation, and this is more important, she added.
</P>
<P>
She called on both sides to respect each other's position
rather than one imposes interest on another.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Association of Southeast Asian nations (ASEAN)
had warned that the momentum of ASEAN's expanding ties with the EU
could be set back if disputes, including East Timor, took center
stage.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Indonesian delegate to the Asia-EU talks Rahardjo
Jamtomo said the ASEAN was united in opposing any discussion on
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony seized by Indonesia in the
mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the seven-member ASEAN and the 15-nation
EU will meet on Thursday and Friday to discuss ways to broaden
their political, economic and cultural ties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
