<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Private Museums Operating in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China plans to add to its more
than 200 private museums by opening to the public collections of
Mao Zedong badges, miniature carvings, tree-root engravings,
first-issue journals, tickets, insects, stones, ship models and
unusual bottles.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the wide variety illustrates the shift in
philosophy of Chinese private collectors, who have long refused to
put their antiques on public display.
</P>
<P>
To date, Shanghai has 20 private museums and Beijing has 10,
including four which will open soon.
</P>
<P>
The "Calculator Museum," China's first individually-sponsored
museum, was opened by Chen Baoding in Shanghai in March of
1981. On show are over 520 Chinese and foreign calculators,
including one abacus that is four meters long and another that is
round and silver.
</P>
<P>
The wave of private collections began in the early 1980s with
the country's reform drive and improved lifestyles. Now the number
of such museums accounts for 16 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
China's first museum opened in 1905, and since then, more than
2,000 state and collectively-run museums have received visitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Scores 97 Billion Yuan in Retail Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital's retail
sector has achieved 97 million yuan (about 11.7 billion US
dollars) in sales volume in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Sources claim there were nearly 70 large retail outlets whose
sales volume scored more than 100 million yuan each, accounting
for 21 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Also in 1996, 57 large stores exceeded 10 million yuan in
profits and taxes, including seven whose gains topped 100 million
yuan, according to Beijing Daily.
</P>
<P>
There are presently 1,300 chain stores in Beijing, a city with
11 million permanent residents and three million transients.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by the end of the century, 100 shopping
centers, each covering more than 10,000 square meters, will be
opened in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
