<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemalan Congress Approves Deployment of UN Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Guatemalan congress
today unanimously approved the deployment of 155 United Nations
military observers to verify compliance of a recent peace accord
which ended 36 years of civil war in the country.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the U.N. mission will be to verify the
demobilization and disarmament of some 3,000 guerrillas from the
Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unit (URNG) who waged a 36-year
war against the government for recognition of economic, social and
land rights for the indigenous population.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of observers comes under the terms of a
definitive cease-fire agreement signed by the government and the
URNG in the Norwegian capital Oslo on December 4, 1996, as part of
negotiations for a final peace treaty which was signed on
December 29.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved the mission on January
20. The observers will be sent to eight zones in the Guatemalan
interior designated as assembly points where the guerrillas are to
surrender their weapons before starting their integration into
civil life.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan government and the guerrillas started peace
negotiations in April 1991 and signed a range of agreements last
year in the run up to the final wide-ranging peace accord signed
on December 29.
</P>
<P>
The deal put an end to the civil war in which some 175,000
people are estimated to have died, with 45,000 missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
