<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Acting President Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's Acting President
Rosalia Arteaga announced her resignation tonight, two days after
she took the office following the ouster of an elected president.
</P>
<P>
Arteaga made her intention public at a press conference while
the country's top legislators, who sacked President Abdala Bucaram
last week, were debating a new replacement to run the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Arteaga was the small Andean nation's vice president until
Congress named her acting president on Sunday to replace Bucaram,
who was voted out by the legislature for "mental incapacity."
</P>
<P>
Before stepping down, Arteaga issued a decree calling for a
national referendum on whether a vice president should succeed the
president if the head of state's position becomes vacant.
</P>
<P>
But as a caretaker president, Arteaga was committed to an
agreement with Congress that she would give way to an interim
president who would call new elections and govern until 1998.
</P>
<P>
She reportedly refused to give up power on Monday but later
changed her mind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
