<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarus Rejects NATO Expansion Plan: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) still lacks justification for its planned
eastward expansion, Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko said
today.
</P>
<P>
As Russia's closest ally within the Commonwealth of Independent
States, Belarus has firmly sided with Russia in opposing NATO's
plans for expanding into eastern Europe since the 16-nation
alliance officially announced its plan in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said Belarus would not question the right of other
countries to join NATO, but hoped that its own stance would be
taken into consideration when the alliance discussed the plans.
</P>
<P>
And he warned there would be a high price to pay if Belarus'
views were ignored.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko pointed out that safeguarding the security of
European countries will be realized by demilitarization in the
region instead of an enlarged military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko made the remarks in a foreign polcy speech at a
government meeting, during which he also mentioned Belarus'
policies on China and Russia, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The president indicated that China and Belarus are political
partners and his country would always treasure such a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
He added that great potential still exists for the two
countries to expand economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
But he said Russia-Belarus relations were his foreign policy's
top priority. Belarus will consistently develop friendship with
Russia so as to benefit the peoples of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
