<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Countries Launch Waterway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay today inaugurated a waterway project which will link the
three countries, increasing freight transport and cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem, Paraguayan President Juan
Wasmosy and Uruguayan President Julio Sanguinetti took part in the
ceremony, which opened work on a 3,440-kilometer waterway
connecting the three neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The project includes dredging a 32-foot deep canal from the
port of San Martin in the Argentine province of Santa Fe to the
Atlantic Ocean, through the Emilio Mitre Canal.
</P>
<P>
Concessions for planned dredging from Santa Fe to the
Paraguayan capital of Asuncion, and the dredging of the Uruguay
River between the Uruguayan city of Concepcion and the Argentine
province of Entre Rios were also announced.
</P>
<P>
The next tender for bids will cover a 1,722-kilometer dredging
project in Argentina, due to be concluded in 1998. The cost for
the first stage of it is estimated at 37 million U.S. dollars and
the annual maintenance cost at 12 million.
</P>
<P>
Once finished, the waterway will connect the Pantanal region on
the Brazilian-Bolivian border with the River de la Plata. It is
hoped that the waterway will allow bigger ships to carry more
freight and at lower cost between the three countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
