<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Depends on Imports for 80 Percent of Consumer Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Still reeling from the
industrial collapse that followed the breakup of the Soviet Union,
Russia depends on imports for 80 percent of its consumer goods, a
top government official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country "is fully dependent on purchases made abroad," a
report of the Itar-Tass news agency today quoted Deputy Economy
Minister Ivan Starikov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a government commission, Starikov said the country
needs to lessen its dependence on foreign goods and attract
investment to develop its own producers.
</P>
<P>
He said that at least 160 countries are exporting goods to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Some officials at the meeting said Russia should impose
protectionist measures to protect domestic industries or increase
taxes upon foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
Russia's economy has been shrinking for six straight years. In
addition, the old Soviet system was not geared to produce the wide
variety of consumer goods people now demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
