<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Government and MRTA Guerillas Start New Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Peru's government and rebels
holding 72 hostages at the Japanese ambassador's residence here
started face-to-face talks today in a bid to resolve the
eight-week crisis.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian government negotiator Domingo Palermo and Rolly Rojas,
second-in-command of the MRTA guerillas, met at a safe house near
the residence for the talks, the first direct negotiations between
the two sides since Palermo, also education minister, met the
leader of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) inside the
ambassador's residence on December 28.
</P>
<P>
The talks are being supervised by a commission of guarantors
set up to negotiate an end to the crisis and made up of
representatives from the Vatican and the International Red Cross,
the Canadian ambassador to Peru and the Japanese ambassador to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The commission announced in a communique that any information
on the talks will be handled with extreme discretion, saying both
sides agreed not to comment publicly over the content of the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
The commission expressed its hope that a peace solution would
be found soon to protect the lives and human dignity of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori was optimistic about a
satisfactory outcome. He hoped talks with Rojas, a sociologist
with the nom de guerre "The Arab", would lead to formal
negotiations in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The hostage crisis started on December 17, 1996, when 22 MRTA
guerrillas took over the Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima,
taking more than 500 cocktail party guests hostage to press for
the release of their 400 comrades jailed in Peru.
</P>
<P>
Most of the hostages have now been freed but the rebels are
still holding 72 key people, including two Peruvian ministers, the
Japanese and Bolivian ambassadors, some Japanese businessmen and
Fujimori's brother. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
