<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company Begins Oil Drilling in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The ARCO of the United States
has begun oil drilling on Myanmar's coast waters after conducting
a seismic survey with the state-run Myanmar Oil and Gas Enterprise
(MOGE).
</P>
<P>
According to today's official paper the New Light of Myanmar,
the drilling is being conducted at the Shwepyihtay test well-1 at
block M-9 as an initial step as the results of the survey work
have indicated good prospects to get oil and gas at the block.
</P>
<P>
The Shwepyihtay test well-1, which is located off Mottama
coast, about 296 kilometers south of Yangon, will be drilled up to
3.2 kilometer depth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company signed the production sharing contract with
the MOGE in July 1995 for exploration of oil and natural gas at
the block.
</P>
<P>
Exploration is also being done at another block, which is M-7,
by the U.S. company under its second contract signed with Myanmar
last May.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Myanmar has signed over 20
production- sharing contracts with oil companies from nearly 10
countries including Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia, Thailand and the United States, and foreign investment
in the oil and gas sector had reached 1.49 billion U.S. dollars in
31 permitted projects as of the end of 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
