<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Limits Coming for Beijing's Large Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital will issue
a blueprint to control the development of large retail outlets --
shopping centers, supermarkets and department stores.
</P>
<P>
The move is to achieve a reasonable distribution of large-scale
retail outlets throughout the city, with an 11 million population,
and to avoid repetitious construction, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
The locations of shopping centers occupying areas of more than
10,000 square meters will have to conform to the city's overall
planning strategy, said Zang Hongge, chairman of the Beijing
Municipal Commercial Commission.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has 66 shopping centers of that size. Another 30 are
under construction.
</P>
<P>
A detailed explanation of Beijing's overall planning policies
will be released soon by the commercial commission to help guide
and regulate the development of local stores.
</P>
<P>
Experts will be called in to re-examine the plans of large
department stores not yet under construction. New projects out of
step with the city's overall planning policy will be halted.
</P>
<P>
To better distribute retail outlets throughout the huge city,
the local government will support the development of retail
outlets in residential areas. Commodity distribution centers for
chain stores and warehouse facilities also will receive official
support to ensure a more reasonable distribution of business
outlets.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has experienced a boom in large department store
construction in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In the Seventh Five-Year Plan period (1986-1990), the city
contained only eight department stores larger than 10,000 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 100 shopping centers, each of more than
10,000 square meters, will be opened in Beijing by the end of the
century.
</P>
<P>
However, the concentration of large department stores in
certain areas and the repetitious offering of identical products
have defeated management plans to achieve their own commercial
goals and caused a serious waste of labor and material resources.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the local commercial commission showed that
among 41 shopping centers which turn over an average of more than
100 million yuan (about 12 million US dollars) per year, 17
experienced a drop in profits in 1996, compared to the previous
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
