<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Control over Rural Enterprises Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- New rural enterprises will
undergo more strict environmental examination before they open to
prevent possible industrial pollution, the Ministry of Agriculture
said.
</P>
<P>
While more than 23 million township enterprises contribute half
of the country's industrial output, they disgorge one-fifth of the
country's waste water, gas and residue, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Their sparse distribution in the vast countryside and urban
areas poses a threat to agricultural development. In this sense,
the ministry's Township Enterprises Bureau has vowed to strengthen
checks on enterprises set to open.
</P>
<P>
Before opening an enterprise, applicants must submit
environmental impact reports on their activities to local
administrative departments, said the bureau's vice-director Zong
Jinyao.
</P>
<P>
Projects, which are considered to be light-polluting within
national limits, are asked to be equipped with pollution-proof
facilities, which must be put into use the same time as the main
projects. Meanwhile, township enterprises are on a national
campaign to change from being resource-dependent to
technology-oriented.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural Bank of China and the National Environmental
Protection Agency said late last month they will grant no loans to
small enterprises with serious pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
By last December, 50,000 rural enterprises, involving
pulp-making, hide-processing, chemical industries and some others
which seriously polluted the environment, had been closed by the
government.
</P>
<P>
With an average 5.7 workers per firm, a total of 285,000 people
will have to be transferred to other business or laid off.
</P>
<P>
Another 10,000 heavy-polluting firms have been blacklisted and
will be closed down.
</P>
<P>
The factories include paper mills with an annual output of less
than 5,000 tons, tanneries producing less than 30,000 pieces of
cow leather annually and factories producing less than 500 tons of
dye a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Rubber Inventory to Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China's rubber supply is
likely to continue to surge this year, but imports will remain
high, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The paper said rubber supply surged 22.6 percent to 1.89
million tons last year, compared with 1.46 million tons in 1995.
Total consumption grew seven percent to 1.4 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The glut of last year will add to this year's rubber supply,"
the paper quoted Chen Guoying, secretary-general of the Chinese
Rubber Industry Association, as saying.
</P>
<P>
China produced 973,000 tons of rubber last year, with synthetic
rubber accounting for 56 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the world's top four rubber consumers. Domestic
supply remains far below demand since China's tyre industry, the
biggest rubber consumer, is thriving.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that rubber imports will stay at around 50
percent of annual consumption.
</P>
<P>
Imports in 1996 hit 917,000 tons, jumping 45.1 percent from
1995. Imports of natural rubber reached 550,000 tons, soaring 72.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The price decline in the international rubber market partly
resulted in the surge in imports last year," said zhao Wenqing,
deputy director of the Ministry of Chemical Industry's rubber
division.
</P>
<P>
The oversupply of rubber last year also prompted a plunge in
the domestic price to around 13,000 yuan (1,566 US dollars) per
ton, down from the record high of 18,000 yuan (2,166 US dollars)
per ton in the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise in rubber prices during 1994-95 left domestic
rubber consumers reeling under the weight of escalating costs.
</P>
<P>
"This year's price is likely to continue decreasing, but at the
same pace as last year," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Total tyre production in 1996 is estimated at 61 million tons,
with unsold stock surging 20 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Despite the slump in tyre production, experts predict rubber
demand will increase five percent to 1.47 million tons this
year. Domestic production is estimated at 1.05 million tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
"The import of rubber, annually accounting for half of the
nation's consumption, will see a slight decline because of last
year's inventory," Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Search for More Agricultural Minerals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Geology and
Mineral Resources is trying to find more minerals which can
facilitate agricultural development, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
These minerals will boost the production of fertilizer, fodder
and pesticides, said Li Lierong, director of the ministry's
Department of Geological Environment.
</P>
<P>
Minerals such as sylvite, phosphorus and sulphur are widely
used abroad to produce fertilizers, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Studies show China will need 150 million tons of fertilizers by
2000.
</P>
<P>
China has discovered 4.3 billion tons of sulphur and iron ore
and 15.7 billion tons of phosphorus ore, enough to meet the demand
for sulphur and phosphorus fertilizer production.
</P>
<P>
Although the ministry discovered 400 million tons of sylvite
ore, more reserves need to be found to produce enough potash
fertilizer by 2000, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also try to discover sufficient mineral
supplies to improve fodder production, Li said.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 minerals which can raise crop or livestock yields
are found in China.
</P>
<P>
Li also said his ministry will study, with agricultural and
chemical departments, the use of minerals in pesticide
production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
