<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage editorial calls on government officials and all
Party members to work arduously and not to be extravagant at the
expense of public funds.
</P>
<P>
-- A feature story describes the building of the 898-kilometer
Nanning-Kunming railway which will open to traffic the coming
July. The railway runs through the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, Guizhou and Yunnan provinces and 15 million poor
population in the three provinces will benefit from the operation
of the railway.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Northwest China's Gansu province helped 1.22 million people
shake off poverty in 1996 by encouraging the building of
water-saving irrigation projects, green houses and fruit tree
bases.
</P>
<P>
-- Liaoning, a northeast province with many large state-owned
enterprises, sped up reform by allowing five enterprises merging
80 other enterprises operating in the red and declaring bankrupt
with 133 enterprises. The province also found jobs for 197,000
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- To prevent possible industrial pollution, rural enterprises
will undergo more strict environmental examinations before they
open, the Ministry of Agriculture said.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources is trying to
find more mineral resources which can facilitate agricultural
development.
</P>
<P>
-- High Technology development zones will be built along the
expressway connecting the cities of Beijing, Tianjin and Tanggu in
north China.  
</P>
