<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, Februaryf 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries over
the past few days:
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- The Nueva Banca, a Cuban financial group, and the
Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC) of Great Britain,
agreed to set up a mixed financial venture "Caribbean Finance
Investment Ltd." on the Cuban island to provide medium-term
financing, according to the Banco Nacional de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The mixed financial venture will operate with five million
U.S. dollars of which 60 percent will be provided by the CDC and
the remaining 40 percent by the Cuban group. Furthermore, the
CDC will grant the new company a medium-term credit line of
another 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaraguan sugar cane workers have expressed their
concern over the possible reduction in their quota of sugar
exports if Mexico convinces the United States to assign it a quota
of 250,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
According to Noel Chamorro, the general manager of the national
committee of sugar cane growers in Nicaragua, in the next few
months a representative of Nicaraguan sugar cane workers will meet
with U.S. authorities in Washington to present a proposal to
censure the signing of the U.S. quota to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA - 1996 revenues for the multinational soft
drink company Coca Cola reached 650 million dollars in Colombia
and its sales volume increased 10 percent while its sales in the
world market increased 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year the company's investments climbed to nearly 100
million dollars of which 40 million corresponded to new products
and industrial processes.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Total sales of household appliances in the Latin
American region grew 17 percent this year and annual rates will
be 7 percent up to the year 2000, pointed out a research study
made by the London-based DKB (Dresdner Kleinwort Benson) financial
institute cited Monday by the local press.
</P>
<P>
The study points out that Brazil will be the biggest market
for household appliances in Latin America and the one with the
greatest potential for growth in the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the sales volume of household appliances in Brazil
showed an increase of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Investments made by Chilean companies abroad
during 1996 reached 1.007 billion dollars which represents an
increase of 24 percent compared with the year before, said
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
More than half of that capital, i.e. 539.6 million dollars, was
oriented towards financial, insurance, real estate and service
establishments followed by 228.8 million dollars for the
manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, which received 655 million dollars, was the main
recipient of Chilean capital. (to be continued)



nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
