<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin american Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 11 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay exported about 5,000 tons of horse meat
worth some 10 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The production of horse meat, which is exported in its entirety
to Europe, is Uruguay's third most important meat product sold
abroad, surpassed only by beef and lamb and followed by poultry.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Russia will resume its purchases of Argentine
meat this year after not having done so during the past 12
years, to substitute its imports of beef from Europe affected by
mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's Agricultural Ministry noted last week that
should this resumption of beef sales be formalized, Argentina will
be able to export a good part of the 650,000 tons of meat that
Russia expects to buy this year, much more than the 500,000 tons
that Argentina is now exporting.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's air freight transportation reported a
growth of 8 percent over the past three years, according to
"Economic Climate of Demand", an analysis made by the Airport
Statistical System.
</P>
<P>
The report states that 1,031,272 tons of air freight were
handled by the national airport system which is administered
by the Airport and Auxiliary Services between 1994-96. with an
annual average of 343,724 tons of consumer products and
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican government revenues increased 24
percent in January compared with the same month in 1996,
according to the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Customs duties showed a big jump in collections, the same as
revenues from income tax which it attributed mainly to coffee
retentions.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, in January the Costa Rican government paid
interest on its internal debts and teachers' salaries,
which together added up to about 10 billion colons (some 45.9
million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
