<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Goes to WTO over Japanese Pork Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has
decided to go to the World Trade Organization for consultations
with Japan over what it regards as Japan's failure to administer
the import of frozen pork in a uniform, impartial and reasonable
manner.
</P>
<P>
The EU made the decision in response to the "emergency
measures' introduced by Japan on pork imports for five months
between November 1 of 1995 and March 31 of last year, according to
a press release issued here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EU claims that the periodic use of emergency import
restrictions by Japan since November 1995 has caused market
disruption, effectively pricing European, mainly Danish, pork
exports out of the Japanese market for most of the year.
</P>
<P>
It believes that the way these emergency measures are being
used contravenes the terms of the Uruguay Round Agreement. Canada
has announced that it will join the EU's request for WTO
consultations.
</P>
<P>
Under the Uruguay Round, any such emergency measure must be
administered in a uniform, impartial and reasonable manner, and
the distribution of tariff quotas should approximately reflect the
market share of the existing suppliers to the market so as to
avoid any discrimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbian Parliament Passes Law to Reinstate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian parliament passed
a special law Tuesday to reinstate the opposition victory in
November's local elections.
</P>
<P>
The law, drafted by the Serbian government under instruction of
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic on February 4, was passed by
130 parliament deputies present at the special session. It
finalizes the preliminary results of municipal elections in
Serbian cities listed in a report by a mission of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe and confirms the victories
of the opposition coalition Zajedno in the local elections.
</P>
<P>
Constituent sessions of the municipal and city assemblies will
be called by the parliament speaker within five days of the
promulgation of the law.
</P>
<P>
The election of deputies is established by municipal elections
commissions, or city election commissions, within three days of
the law taking effect.
</P>
<P>
If the election commissions fail to comply within the mentioned
period of time, the ministry of justice will establish the
individual election of deputies within the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
The law takes effect the day after it is published in the
Serbian official gazette.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government hopes that the law would end the
political crisis that was sparked off by a court ruling to annul
the local election results since November 19 when the opposition
took to the streets to protest over the annulment.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition, while welcoming the adoption of the
special law, continued their street protest on Tuesday that began
82 days ago. Zajedno leaders say they would not cease their
demonstrations until all their demands were met, that include the
freedom of mass media and democracy in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved two
loans of 283 million U.S. dollars in total for Peru to help it
reduce debt to commercial banks and private suppliers.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement of the Bank, one loan of 183
million U.S. dollars is entitled Debt and Debt Service Reduction
loan, and the other loan of 100 million U.S. dollars is called
Pension Reform Adjustment loan.
</P>
<P>
These loans will support Peru's finance agreement with its
private creditors that will restructure 7.98 billion U.S. dollars
of its commercial debt. The combined loan agreements are a vital
step in further consolidating the country's economic recovery and
financial stability, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the finance plan the Peruvian government agreed
with its foreign private creditors and being supported by the
World Bank goes a long way to further integrate Peru into the
international financial community and confirm investor confidence
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
