<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Surges High Against Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a
33-month high against the mark Tuesday in a broad rally.
</P>
<P>
Widespread mark weakness and an underlying demand for dollars
spurred the advance of the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar reached an intraday high of 1.6810 marks, the
strongest since May 1994, before settling in New York at 1.6766
marks, up from 1.6560 marks Monday. For the year, the dollar is up
nearly 8.8 percent against the mark.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar settled in New York at 123.15 yen, up from
122.78 yen Monday, and only 1.55 yen lower than its intraday
four-year high reached last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The pound weakened to 1.6369 U.S. dollars from 1.6407 U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Defends Foreign Affairs Budget Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today defended a budget increase on foreign
affairs, proposed by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"During the last four years, the State Department has cut more
than 2,000 employees and closed more than 30 overseas posts, and
we have slashed foreign assistance by almost one third," Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
"This trend cannot continue," she told the House of
Representatives International Relations Committee, adding that
"diplomatically, we are steadily and unilaterally disarming
ourselves" under such current trends.
</P>
<P>
"Spending on international affairs now constitutes barely one
percent of the federal budget," she added.
</P>
<P>
"If this small amount were to be cut further, it is out
influence in the world, not the deficit, that would decline," she
said. "Diplomatic readiness is not a luxury; it is an imperative."
</P>
<P>
In his budget plan for the fiscal year of 1998 sent to Congress
last week for approval, Clinton proposed an increase of over six
percent over 1997 to a total of 19.4 billion U.S. dollars for
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Gilman, chairman of the House International Relations
Committee, told Albright that Congress was ready to work with her
on the budget plan.
</P>
<P>
The budget request, plus a 3.5 billion U.S. dollars "general
agreement to borrow" for the International Monetary Fund and 920
million dollars arrears payment for the United Nations by 1999, is
certainly "a tall order", Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright also issues new appeal for NATO
enlargement. A long delay in expanding NATO would create a
"permanent source of tension and insecurity in the heart of
Europe", she testified before the Committee.
</P>
<P>
The "right approach", she stressed, is to proceed with a
"careful and transparent" process of expansion while "offering to
Russia the opportunity to be a full partner".
</P>
<P>
"To that end, NATO has proposed a formal charter to Russia that
will allow us to cooperate, consult, train and respond to crises
together," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made steady progress toward this goal, which will be a
major subject of my discussions in Europe," she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 11 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks turned mostly
higher late in today's session as the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 51.57 points to 6,858.11.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with the NYSE volume up to 480.59
million shares as against 467.54 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.16 to 789.59, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 1.74 to 414.09.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 3.99 to 1,331.35, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 1.40 to 589.24.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's late advance was ignited by United Technologies,
which surged the equivalent of 10 Dow points. The Dow also drew a
boost from a partial rebound by DuPont and IBM.  
</P>
</TEXT>
