<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Considers Situation in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today considered the latest development of
situation in Liberia and called on all interested parties to help
push the peace process in the African country.
</P>
<P>
The Council focused discussions on the 21st report of the U.N.
Secretary-General on the United Nations Observer Mission in
Liberia(UNOMIL), particularly on the progress of and disarmament
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Njuguna Mahugo, current President of the U.N. Security Council,
said in a statement after the consultations that members of the
Council were encouraged by recent positive developments in Liberia
and urged all parties in the country to "continue cooperating with
ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West African States) and UNOMIL
in pushing forward peace process.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concerns about humanitarian situation and continuing
cease-fire violations, the statement called on all parties
concerned in Liberia to fulfill their obligations under the Abuja
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned the employment of child soldiers and
demand their immediate release for demobilization.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that members of the Security Council were
determined to "follow very closely" the process leading to free
and fair elections and to the establishment of a genuine
democratic base.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed hope that the forthcoming ECOWAS
ministerial meeting scheduled for mid-February in Monrovia will
set a timetable for the elections in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS and UNOMIL have been working together in the past few
years in assisting the Liberians to establish peace in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
