<HEADLINE> Albright Defends Foreign Affairs Budget Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today defended a budget increase on foreign
affairs, proposed by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"During the last four years, the State Department has cut more
than 2,000 employees and closed more than 30 overseas posts, and
we have slashed foreign assistance by almost one third," Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
"This trend cannot continue," she told the House of
Representatives International Relations Committee, adding that
"diplomatically, we are steadily and unilaterally disarming
ourselves" under such current trends.
</P>
<P>
"Spending on international affairs now constitutes barely one
percent of the federal budget," she added.
</P>
<P>
"If this small amount were to be cut further, it is out
influence in the world, not the deficit, that would decline," she
said. "Diplomatic readiness is not a luxury; it is an imperative."
</P>
<P>
In his budget plan for the fiscal year of 1998 sent to Congress
last week for approval, Clinton proposed an increase of over six
percent over 1997 to a total of 19.4 billion U.S. dollars for the
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Gilman, the chairman of the House International
Relations Committee, told Albright that Congress was ready to work
with her on the budget plan.
</P>
<P>
The budget request, plus a 3.5 billion U.S. dollars "general
agreement to borrow" for the International Monetary Fund and 920
million dollars arrears payment for the United Nations by 1999, is
certainly "a tall order", Gilman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
