<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Official Hits Back at Critics of EU Social Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A European Union commissioner
today hit back at those who blame the Union for over-regulation
which they claim have been killing business.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, EU commissioner in charge of employment and
social affairs, struck the counterblow when he was speaking
Tuesday in Brussels to the British Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that today's reality consisted of
navigating a path between "the rabid deregulators, who offer us
the low pay, low productivity route and those within an equally
rigid view of social progress, who see change as anathema and
offer us only the high unemployment...and dual labor market
route."
</P>
<P>
What is needed is "new approaches to skills, work organization
and re-integration into the labor market...new partnerships
between government, business and organized labor, and a new focus
on investment in people for productivity growth and competitive
success," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner pointed out that social legislation was mainly
a matter for national authorities and that provision at European
level was only concerned with equal opportunities, free movement
of workers, health and safety in the workplace and classic labor
law.
</P>
<P>
He said that a competitive economy could not be created in a
social wasteland, adding that they should not oversimplify any
change in the EU's social policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
