<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Americans to Respect Simpson Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today urged the Americans to respect to the O.J. Simpson jury
verdict despite the general disagreement between the blacks and
whites on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
"It terms of the jury verdict, that's the system we have in
America. It's over as far as I'm concerned," Clinton said in a
brief exchange with reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"We need to get on to other things. But we always need to be
working on how to bridge these divides between us," Clinton said,
asking the blacks and whites to "spend more than listening to each
other."
</P>
<P>
A mostly white jury decided on last Tuesday that Simpson was
responsible for the slayings of his ex-wife Nicole Brown Simpson
and her friend Ronald Goldman two and a half years ago. The same
jury again decided on Monday to impose a 25 million U.S. dollar
punishment on the former football star for the slayings, based on
a 8.5 million dollars in compensatory damages awarded last week.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, a mostly black jury acquitted Simpson of
criminal charges in October 1995. After the jury's decision,
Clinton also said Americans should respect the verdict, concerning
the racial disagreement in the country.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion polls show that most white Americans believed
Simpson committed the murders while a majority of blacks believed
he was innocent.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of the way Americans see the world differently,
generally, based on their race, that troubles me," Clinton said
today. "I think the only answer to that is for us to spend more
time listening to each other and try to put ourselves in each
other's shoes and understand why we see the world in different
ways and keep trying to overcome that."
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of social harmony in the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
