<HEADLINE> Milosevic Meets with Klein on Eastern Slavonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic held talks here Tuesday with U.N. Administrator of the
Eastern Slavonia region Jacques Klein over the regional situation.
</P>
<P>
A Serbian presidential office said in a statement that the two
sides exchanged views on further implementation of the Erdut
agreement, signed in November 1995 between local Serb authority in
Eastern Slavonia and the Croatian government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Eastern Slavonia region, located in
northeastern Croatia bordering Yugoslavia and dominated by
Croatian Serbs, was put under the U.N. Transitional Administration
in the Eastern Slavonia (UNTAES) for 12 months since early 1996.
The transitional period has been extended for another six months
and the U.N. mandate expires in next July if no further extension
was demanded by local Serbs.
</P>
<P>
At the talks, Milosevic stressed the importance of the
Serb-Croatian relations in the region, and called for a consistent
implementation of the Erdut agreement which will be an important
element of the promotion of those relations, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the U.N. transitional administration is of great
importance and that is why administrator Klein and his team are
expected to show the necessary understanding for constructive
proposals and demands of the Serb side," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian president also stressed that the U.N. transitional
administration should especially help create an atmosphere of
confidence, personal security, security of the property, and equal
rights of citizens in the region.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic also asked for creating conditions for an
equality-based participation of all inhabitants in the upcoming
elections in the Eastern Slavonia region, so that the elections
could be held in a democratic atmosphere and could be free and
fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
