<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's UN Envoy Demands Speedier Delivery of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 11 (Xinhua) --Iraq's envoy to the
United Nations has complained that food supplies under an
"oil-for-food" plan were taking too long to arrive, and urged the
United Nations to take effective measures for speedier delivery of
the supplies, U.N. sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's U.N. envoy Nizar Hamdoon lodged the complaints when
meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan late Monday, the
sources said. He also appealed to non-aligned members of the U.N.
Security Council today to support his demand for quicker delivery
of the food supplies.
</P>
<P>
Under the "oil-for-food" agreement which took effect on
December 10, Iraq has been permitted to sell 2 billion U.S.
dollars worth of oil over six months to buy food, medicine and
other necessaries to offset the effects of U.N. sanctions imposed
after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. Some 155 U.N.
monitors have been sent to Iraq to ensure equitable distribution
of the humanitarian food and medicine supplies.
</P>
<P>
But Hamdoon told reporters Monday that no food supplies had
reached his country, and the U.N. Security Council's sanction
committee was slow in approving the supply plans and deliveries.
</P>
<P>
In response, Annan's spokesman Fred Eckhard told reporters at
the press briefing today that the U.N. chief had promised to give
Iraq more details on the deliveries and asked Hamdoon to relay
"operational" matters to the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
Some U.N. sources complained that Baghdad was "hindering
operations" for the food supplies on the ground.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the operational issues included
getting permission to use the airport in Baghdad rather than drive
goods and personnel in from Jordan, allowing U.N. monitors to have
their own communications and letting them move around freely
without a Iraqi government escort.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard admitted that Iraq's oil sales had reached 386 million
U.S. dollars but only 113 million U.S. dollars had been dispersed.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that four contracts for foodstuffs had been
approved, including 21 million U.S. dollars for French wheat and
50 million U.S. dollars for Australian wheat.
</P>
<P>
Taking up Iraq's complaint, Russia has asked U.N. officials to
give the Security Council a briefing later this week on precisely
what food supplies were in the pipeline and when they could reach
Iraq, diplomats said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
