<DOCNO> XIE19970212.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spread of HIV Affects Canadian Youth, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The epidemic of HIV infection
appears to be growing in Canada, especially among drug users and
young people.
</P>
<P>
The median age for new infections is now 23, down from 32 in
the early 1980s when the epidemic first hit Canada, the Globe and
Mail newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The lowering of age means that a great number of people now
being diagnosed with HIV must have been infected as teenagers,
since there can be a long delay between contracting the virus and
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
The majority of all HIV infections probably begin in the peak
years of sexual activity, between 15 and 25, and many of those
infected tended to ignore the dangers of contracting AIDS out of
bravado, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the rate of new infections has declined
dramatically among older Canadians, who are apparently taking
precautions.
</P>
<P>
A number of recent statistical analyses show a rising rate of
infection with HIV, which causes AIDS, the paper said. It didn't
give specific figures for the rate.
</P>
<P>
By September 30, 1996, at least 72 percent of the 14,185
Canadians with AIDS reported have died. Another 10,000 to 12,000
cases are expected to be reported through the year 2000, the paper
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
