<HEADLINE> U.S. Studies WFP's Appeal for DPRK Food Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
considering to contribute emergency food aid to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) in response to a new appeal from
the U.N. World Food Program for urgent international assistance,
the State Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the World Food Program, in its third
international appeal ever since the past year, asked the
international community to provide a total of 100,000 metric tons
of food, valued at 41.6 million US dollars, for relief of grain
shortage in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said: "I
understand the World Food Program today issued a new emergency
appeal for humanitarian assistance to North Korea. The World Food
Program is seeking donations of 100,000 metric tons of food valued
at roughly 41.6 million dollars."
</P>
<P>
Burns said the Clinton administration was "very seriously"
studying the request but would consult with allies like South
Korea and Japan before deciding whether and how much to
contribute. A senior official, speaking anonymously, said: "I
believe the United States will make decision to contribute."
</P>
<P>
Burns stressed the humanitarian relief would not be linked to
other issues such as negotiations between the DPRK and Cargill
Inc. a Minnesota-based grain trader, which has run aground over a
deal of importing 500,000 tons of grain to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
He said the breakdown of the negotiations had no bearing on a
decision to contribute to the World Food Program effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
