<HEADLINE> Serbian Cabinet Reshuffled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian government was
reshuffled Tuesday at the proposal of Serbian Premier Mirko
Marjanovic with one vice-premier and nine new ministers being
brought into the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle was made at the Serbian parliament session which
is also expected to approve a "special law" on the reinstatement
of the election results annulled in November by the Serbian
government.
</P>
<P>
Serbia and Montenegro, the two leftover republics of the former
Yugoslavia, formed the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in April of
1992 after the other four republics -- Slovenia, Croatia,
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Macedonia -- gained independence in 1991
and early 1992.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet change was apparently a concession of the Serbian
government under pressure from the opposition coalition Zajedno
which has led daily demonstrations over the past 80 days to
protest against the Serbian government for annulling the November
local election results.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanjug news agency, Milutin Stojkovic, former
assembly speaker of Serbia's northern province Vojvodina, was
appointed vice-premier to replace Slobodan Babic, who was relieved
of post.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of mining and power industry, tourism, industry,
education and agriculture were replaced with new faces while heads
of three newly-formed ministries -- economic and ownership
transformation, self-government and family care -- were appointed.
A minister without portfolio was added into the cabinet, and the
ministry for private entrepreneurship was dissolved.
</P>
<P>
In the new cabinet, there are a prime minister, four
vice-premiers, and 26 ministers, including three ministers without
portfolio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
